{"title_page": "The Midnight Gospel", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = The Midnight Gospel\n| image                    = File:The Midnight Gospel promotional poster.jpg\n| caption                  = Promotional poster\n| genre                    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Adult animation]]\n* [[Surrealism]]\n* [[Science fantasy]]\n* [[Dark comedy]]\n* [[Adventure fiction|Adventure]]\n* [[Interview]]\n}}\n| director                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Pendleton Ward\n* Mike L. Mayfield {{small|(supervising)}}\n}}\n| creator                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Pendleton Ward]]\n* [[Duncan Trussell]]\n}}\n| voices                   = {{Plainlist|\n* Duncan Trussell\n* [[Phil Hendrie]]\n}}\n| theme_music_composer     = \n| opentheme                = \n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = [[Joe Wong (musician)|Joe Wong]]\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 1\n| num_episodes             = 8\n| list_episodes            = \n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Pendleton Ward\n* Duncan Trussell\n* Antonio Canobbio\n* Ben Kalina\n* Chris Prynoski\n}}\n| producer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Shannon Prynoski\n* Tony Salama\n}}\n| editor                   = Megan Love\n| cinematography           = \n| runtime                  = 20-36 minutes\n| company                  = [[Titmouse, Inc.]]\n| distributor              = \n| channel                  = [[Netflix]]\n| picture_format           = [[4K resolution|4K]] ([[Ultra-high-definition television|Ultra HD]])<br>[[High-dynamic-range video|High dynamic range]]\n| audio_format             = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2020|4|20}}\n| last_aired               = present\n| website                  = https://www.netflix.com/title/80987903\n}}\n\n'''''The Midnight Gospel''''' is an [[United States|American]] [[adult animated]] web television series created by ''[[Adventure Time]]''{{'s}} [[Pendleton Ward]] and comedian [[Duncan Trussell]]. It is the first animated production from Ward for [[Netflix]]. Set in Chromatic Ribbon, a spacecaster named Clancy owns an illegal multiverse simulator. Through it, he travels through worlds about to have their own apocalypses interviewing some of their residents for their spacecast.<ref name=\"Countdown\">{{cite web |last1=Flook |first1=Ray |title=The Midnight Gospel Transmits Countdown Clock from Chromatic Ribbon|url=https://bleedingcool.com/tv/the-midnight-gospel-transmits-countdown-clock-from-chromatic-ribbon/ |website=[[Bleeding Cool]] |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> The show features special guests like [[Phil Hendrie]], [[Stephen Root]], [[Drew Pinsky]], Trudy Goodman, Jason Louv, [[Caitlin Doughty]], [[Damien Echols]], [[David Nichtern]], and Deneen Fendig.\n\nThe show debuted on April 20, 2020 on Netflix.\n\n==Synopsis==\n''The Midnight Gospel'' revolves around a spacecaster (video podcaster in space) named Clancy Gilroy who lived in a dimension called \"The Chromatic Ribbon,\" where simulation farmers use powerful bio-computers to simulate universes to harvest technology. <ref name=\"AnMag\"/> Every episode resolves around Clancy travels through planets within the simulator are going through their own unique apocalypses, and the beings living in these other worlds are the guests Clancy interviews for his spacecast.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/streaming/netflix-nabs-new-show-from-adventure-time-creator-pen-ward/|title=Netflix Nabs New Show from 'Adventure Time' Creator Pen Ward|website=[[Animation Magazine]]|first=Ramin|last=Zahed|date=December 19, 2019|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nerdist.com/article/the-midnight-gospel-trailer/|title=The Midnight Gospel Looks Like a Trippier ADVENTURE TIME|website=[[Nerdist Industries|Nerdist]]|first=Eric|last=Diaz|date=March 16, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2020/3/16/21181860/the-midnight-gospel-netflix-adventure-time-release-date-trailer|title=Trailer for Adventure Time creator's latest is a delightfully weird romp through the multiverse|first=Petrana|last=Radulovic|date=March 16, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]}}</ref> These interviews are based on the real interviews derived from Trussell's podcasts interviews that were added to the show with addiction of psychedelic apocalyptic tapestry of the animation.<ref name= \"CBRIn\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbr.com/interview-duncan-trussell-midnight-gospel/|title=Midnight Gospel's Trussell Explains The Show's Intensely Personal Last Episode|first=Reuben|last=Baron|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020|website=[[CBR.com]]}}</ref>\n\n==Cast and characters==\n===Main===\n* [[Duncan Trussell]] as Clancy Gilroy\n\n===Recurring===\n* [[Phil Hendrie]] as Universe Simulator and various characters\n* [[Stephen Root]] as Bill Taft and various characters\n* [[Maria Bamford]] as Butt Demon and various characters\n* [[Doug Lussenhop]] as Daniel Hoops and various characters\n* [[Joey Diaz|Joey \"Coco\" Diaz]] as Chuck Charles and various characters\n* [[Christina Pazsitzky|Christina P.]] as Bobua and various characters\n* [[Steve Little (actor)|Steve Little]] as Captain Bryce and various characters\n* [[Johnny Pemberton]] as Cornelius and various characters\n\n===Guest stars===\n* [[Drew Pinsky]] as Little President (Episode 1 and Episode 5)\n* [[Anne Lamott]] as Anne Deer Dog (Episode 2)\n* Raghu Markas as Raghu Deer Dog (Episode 2)\n* [[Damien Echols]] as Darryl the Fish (Episode 3)\n* Trudy Goodman as Trudy the Love Barbarian (Episode 4)\n* Jason Louv as Jason (Episode 5)\n* [[David Nichtern]] as His Divine Grace, God's Scientist (Episode 1) and David (Episode 6)\n* [[Caitlin Doughty]] as Death (Episode 7)\n* Deneen Fendig as herself aka Duncan's mom and Clancy's mom (Episode 8)\n* [[Ram Dass]] as Ram Dass (Episode 8)\n\n==Episodes==\n===Season 1 (2020)===\n{{Episode table |background=#FEDA4A |overall=5 |season=5 |title=26 |director=12 |writer=35 |aux2=14 |airdate=17 |aux2T=Interview Subject(s) |released=y |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 1\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n| Title           = Taste of the King\n| DirectedBy      = Pendleton Ward\n| WrittenBy       = Mike L. Mayfield, Duncan Trussell and Pendleton Ward\n| Aux2            = [[Drew Pinsky]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|04|20}}\n| ShortSummary    = Clancy visits Earth 4-169, which happens to be in the midst of a zombie apocalypse. Clancy decides to interview the sim Glasses Man, who he discovers is, in fact, the President in this universe. In front of the White House, a group of anti-marijuana protesters are gathered, seemingly unbothered by the zombies around them. This sparks debate between Clancy and Glasses Man as to whether there is such a thing as a 'good drug' or a 'bad drug'. Over the course of the episode, the two discuss the pros and cons of psychedelics, the dangers of drug usage if not well educated, and whether or not drugs can be beneficial for an individual's personal spiritual growth. They end up helping a pregnant woman give birth before they are all turned into zombies. However, they find the new situation relieving. This does not last long as they are hit with a cure that, ironically, causes those still left as zombies to devour them. Clancy returns to his dimension as the Earth explodes.\n| LineColor       = FEDA4A\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 2\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n| Title           = Officers and Wolves\n| DirectedBy      = Pendleton Ward \n| WrittenBy       = Mike L. Mayfield, Duncan Trussell, Brendon Walsh and Pendleton Ward\n| Aux2            = [[Anne Lamott]] and Raghu Markus\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|04|20}}\n| ShortSummary    = On a planet populated by baby clowns, Clancy hears a deer-dog's thoughts on death as they head to a slaughterhouse.\n| LineColor       = FEDA4A\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 3\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n| Title           = Hunters Without a Home\n| DirectedBy      = Pendleton Ward\n| WrittenBy       = Mike L. Mayfield, Duncan Trussell and Pendleton Ward\n|Aux2             = [[Damien Echols]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|04|20}}\n| ShortSummary    = Clancy zaps to an underwater planet, where he crosses paths with Darryl, a student of ceremonial magic and the path to enlightenment. \n| LineColor       = FEDA4A\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 4\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n| Title           = Blinded by my End\n| DirectedBy      = Pendleton Ward \n| WrittenBy       = Meredith Kecskemety, Mike L. Mayfield, Duncan Trussell and Pendleton Ward\n| Aux2            = Trudy Goodman\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|04|20}}\n| ShortSummary    = A mishap sends Clancy to a medieval planet, where he rides along with a knight on a mission to avenge her lover's murder.\n| LineColor       = FEDA4A\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 5\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 5\n| Title           = Annihilation of Joy\n| DirectedBy      = Pendleton Ward \n| WrittenBy       = Mike L. Mayfield, Duncan Trussell and Pendleton Ward\n| Aux2            = Jason Louv\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|04|20}}\n| ShortSummary    = At a prison for simulated beings suffering from existential dread, Clancy ponders reality as he watches an inmate perish over and over.\n| LineColor       = FEDA4A\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 6\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 6\n| Title           = Vulture With Honor\n| DirectedBy      = Pendleton Ward \n| WrittenBy       = Mike L. Mayfield, Duncan Trussell and Pendleton Ward\n| Aux2            = [[David Nichtern]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|04|20}}\n| ShortSummary    = When his simulator malfunctions, Clancy is forced to face a few real-world problems. Later, he meets a meditation master. \n| LineColor       = FEDA4A\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 7\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 7\n| Title           = Turtles of the Eclipse\n| DirectedBy      = Pendleton Ward\n| WrittenBy       = Mike L. Mayfield, Duncan Trussell and Pendleton Ward\n| Aux2            = [[Caitlin Doughty]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|04|20}}\n| ShortSummary    = A boring trip takes a remarkable turn when Clancy accidentally falls into another world - and comes face to face with Death.\n| LineColor       = FEDA4A\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 8\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 8\n| Title           = Mouse of Silver\n| DirectedBy      = Pendleton Ward\n| WrittenBy       = Mike L. Mayfield, Duncan Trussell and Pendleton Ward\n| Aux2            = Deneen Fendig\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|04|20}}\n| ShortSummary    = Clancy joins his mother on an emotional journey through the wondrous cycle of birth, life and death.\n| LineColor       = FEDA4A\n}}\n}}\n\n==Production==\n===Concept and creation===\nDuring the start of his podcast broadcast (around 2013), Trussel received an email from Ward praising him for his podcast.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Prudom |first1=Laura |title=Netflix's The Midnight Gospel: Exclusive First Look at Adventure Time Creator's Adult Animated Series|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/netflix-the-midnight-gospel-release-date-trailer-adventure-time |website=[[IGN]] |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> About a year later, Ward left \"[[Adventure Time]]\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Strauss |first1=Neil |title=\u2018Adventure Time\u2019: The Trippiest Show on Television|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/tv-news/adventure-time-the-trippiest-show-on-television-84180/ |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |date=October 2, 2014}}</ref> Despite saying in an interview that he would not work on another series, Ward was taking the first steps in a new series anchored in the adaptation of Trussell's podcast. Some time later Trussell and Ward became friends and Ward suggested to Trussell to turn his podcast into an animated series. According to Ward, Trussell had the ability to make 2 hours of a meditation conversation funny. Trussell says: \"He reached out to me and said he had an idea for how to animate my podcast, which was another big thrill for me.\"<ref name=\"Inverse\">{{cite web |last1=Kleinman |first1=Jake |title='Midnight Gospel' Was Seven Years In The Making. Here's How It Finally Happened.|url=https://www.inverse.com/entertainment/midnight-gospel-netflix-duncan-trussell-pendleton-ward |website=[[Inverse (website)|Inverse]]|accessdate=April 20, 2020 |date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> In the first meeting with Ward, Trussell declined to join to a new project claiming he was too busy to turn his podcast into an animated show. In 2018, Ward approached to him again to show a rough concept taking a podcast conversation about drug addiction and playing it over an animatic of Trussell and his guest fighting off a zombie invasion.<ref name=\"Inverse\"/>\n\nLater, the rough of concept ended up being incorporated into the pilot of the series. The two took the concept of the series in pitching form to Mike Moon, head of adult animations at Netflix. In 2019, Netflix has ordered eight episodes, which is slated to premiere in sometime in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/netflix-order-adult-animated-series-the-midnight-gospel-from-pendleton-ward-duncan-trussell-1202814276/|title=Netflix Orders Adult Animated Series \u2018The Midnight Gospel\u2019 From Pendleton Ward & Duncan Trussell|website=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]]|first1=Denise|last1=Petski|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=December 19, 2019}}</ref> After gaining the green light, the two gathered a team of comedians like [[Johnny Pemberton]], Brendon Walsh, [[\"Weird Al\" Yankovic]] and [[Emo Philips]] were joined by occult scholar Jason Louv and white witch Maja D\u2019Aoust. The two assembled a team of approximately 190 people at Titmouse and started working on creating the episodes.<ref name=\"AnMag\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/streaming/light-at-the-end-of-the-apocalypse-pen-ward-duncan-trussell-preach-the-midnight-gospel/|title=Light at the End of the Apocalypse: Pen Ward & Duncan Trussell Preach 'The Midnight Gospel'|website=Animation Magazine|first=Ramin|last=Zahed|date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> Mike Mayfield joined the project as supervising director and writer for all the episodes. The team behind the show are composed by Jesse Moynihan (art director), Antonio Canobbio (Chief Creative Officer for Titmouse), Mike Roush (animation director) and Joey Adams (storyboard supervisor). Mayfield said that the time needed to \"try something nine different ways before one little change would make it go from clunky to incredible.\"<ref name=\"AnMag\"/>\n\nDuring the beginning of production was they need to know how much of the episodes will be story to how much will be a podcast conversation, and they also need to choose which parts of the podcast to use in the show. According to Trussell the parts of podcast who entered the series are about highlighting revelatory moments from his career. Trussell said: \u201cWhen I\u2019m doing a podcast, there are moments where my whole universe changes because someone told me something that I never knew. Once you hear that, you\u2019re forever changed; you live in a completely different dimension than you lived in before.\u201d<ref name=\"The Daily Beast\">{{cite web |last1=Schager|first1=Nick |title=From the minds of \u201cAdventure Time\u201d creator Pendleton Ward and podcaster Duncan Trussell comes this fantastically beautiful head-trip of a show. |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/the-midnight-gospel-on-netflix-is-trippy-horny-and-the-next-great-animated-show |website=[[The Daily Beast]]|accessdate=April 20, 2020 |date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> The main challenge of writing the episodes, besides choosing the best interviews, was making them coherent for animation. They also worked to find a way to embed them in psychedelic apocalyptic tapestry of the animation. The episodes should have a balance so that the animation does not take people out of the interview. With an excessive focus on animation people would not pay attention to everything at the same time. The team worked to let the conversations react with the world.<ref name=\"CBRIn\"/> According Trussell the influence for The Midnight Gospel come from [[Adult Swim]] lo-fi aesthetic in general and shows like Space Ghost: Coast 2 Coast and [[Aqua Teen Hunger Force]]. Others shows included [[Watership Down]], [[The Last Unicorn]], Liquid Television; Aeon Flux and [[David Lynch]] was a big influence in how when you watch [[Twin Peak]].<ref name=\"CBRIn\"/>\n\nFor Ward, that it was Trussell\u2019s long-form audio chats that inspired him to return to TV animation <ref name=\"The Daily Beast\"/> and the new series was a chance to explore the brave, new world of making animation for grown-ups. Until then he had made animations for children only and the new show would be a chance to change his way of making animations using the ultra-violence of cartoons with conversations on compassion. Ward also allowed Trussell to include his own original music in several episodes. The show's title came from the good news sense of the word gospel. Trussell says \"\u2019Gospel\u2019 means good news, and I was hoping that we convey the message that even through the most catastrophic situations, when everything is falling part, there is opportunity to grow as a person.\u201d<ref name=\"AnMag\"/>\n\nA second season for the show is uncertain. According to Trussell \"[the world of the Chromatic Ribbon] is a very big world. I spent a long time with Pen working out all the details. Some people might see it and think some people are saying gibberish, that somewhat was absurd and unintended, but every brick in that structure, every piece of the puzzle is intentional and based on a lot of lore. It's a very, very, very, very interesting big world, and I would love to explore that world for as long as I possibly can.\"<ref name=\"CBRIn\"/>\n\n===Marketing===\nThe first teaser was released on March 16, and the main trailer on April 6. As part of promoting the show, Netflix's YouTube channel launched a livestream on April 19, 2020 with a countdown to the series' debut on the streaming service. Throughout the livestream, small portions of the episodes were shown as well as a psychedelic animation.<ref name=\"Countdown\"/>\n\n==Release==\nThe eight-episode first season, ordered by [[Netflix]], was released on April 20, 2020. According to Trussell, the Netflix executives first suggested dropping the series on the unofficial stoner holiday and Ward suggests putting the show out on 4/20. The date is Trussell's birthday and [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]]-oriented celebrations that take place annually on April 20.<ref name=\"The Daily Beast\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|11639414}}\n\n{{Netflix original current series}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Midnight Gospel}}\n[[Category:2020 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2020s animated television series]]\n[[Category:American adult animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n[[Category:Surrealist television series]]\n[[Category:Television series by Netflix Animation]]\n[[Category:Television series created by Pendleton Ward]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = The Midnight Gospel\n| image                    = File:The Midnight Gospel promotional poster.jpg\n| caption                  = Promotional poster\n| genre                    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Adult animation]]\n* [[Surrealism]]\n* [[Science fantasy]]\n* [[Dark comedy]]\n* [[Adventure fiction|Adventure]]\n* [[Interview]]\n}}\n| director                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Pendleton Ward\n* Mike L. Mayfield {{small|(supervising)}}\n}}\n| creator                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Pendleton Ward]]\n* [[Duncan Trussell]]\n}}\n| voices                   = {{Plainlist|\n* Duncan Trussell\n* [[Phil Hendrie]]\n}}\n| theme_music_composer     = \n| opentheme                = \n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = [[Joe Wong (musician)|Joe Wong]]\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 1\n| num_episodes             = 8\n| list_episodes            = \n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Pendleton Ward\n* Duncan Trussell\n* Antonio Canobbio\n* Ben Kalina\n* Chris Prynoski\n}}\n| producer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Shannon Prynoski\n* Tony Salama\n}}\n| editor                   = Megan Love\n| cinematography           = \n| runtime                  = 20-36 minutes\n| company                  = [[Titmouse, Inc.]]\n| distributor              = \n| channel                  = [[Netflix]]\n| picture_format           = [[4K resolution|4K]] ([[Ultra-high-definition television|Ultra HD]])<br>[[High-dynamic-range video|High dynamic range]]\n| audio_format             = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2020|4|20}}\n| last_aired               = present\n| website                  = https://www.netflix.com/title/80987903\n}}\n\n'''''The Midnight Gospel''''' is an [[United States|American]] [[adult animated]] web television series created by ''[[Adventure Time]]''{{'s}} [[Pendleton Ward]] and comedian [[Duncan Trussell]]. It is the first animated production from Ward for [[Netflix]]. Set in Chromatic Ribbon, a spacecaster named Clancy owns an illegal multiverse simulator. Through it, he travels through worlds about to have their own apocalypses interviewing some of their residents for their spacecast.<ref name=\"Countdown\">{{cite web |last1=Flook |first1=Ray |title=The Midnight Gospel Transmits Countdown Clock from Chromatic Ribbon|url=https://bleedingcool.com/tv/the-midnight-gospel-transmits-countdown-clock-from-chromatic-ribbon/ |website=[[Bleeding Cool]] |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> The show features special guests like [[Phil Hendrie]], [[Stephen Root]], [[Drew Pinsky]], Trudy Goodman, Jason Louv, [[Caitlin Doughty]], [[Damien Echols]], [[David Nichtern]], and Deneen Fendig.\n\nThe show debuted on April 20, 2020 on Netflix.\n\n==Synopsis==\n''The Midnight Gospel'' revolves around a spacecaster (video podcaster in space) named Clancy Gilroy who lived in a dimension called \"The Chromatic Ribbon,\" where simulation farmers use powerful bio-computers to simulate universes to harvest technology. <ref name=\"AnMag\"/> Every episode resolves around Clancy travels through planets within the simulator are going through their own unique apocalypses, and the beings living in these other worlds are the guests Clancy interviews for his spacecast.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/streaming/netflix-nabs-new-show-from-adventure-time-creator-pen-ward/|title=Netflix Nabs New Show from 'Adventure Time' Creator Pen Ward|website=[[Animation Magazine]]|first=Ramin|last=Zahed|date=December 19, 2019|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nerdist.com/article/the-midnight-gospel-trailer/|title=The Midnight Gospel Looks Like a Trippier ADVENTURE TIME|website=[[Nerdist Industries|Nerdist]]|first=Eric|last=Diaz|date=March 16, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2020/3/16/21181860/the-midnight-gospel-netflix-adventure-time-release-date-trailer|title=Trailer for Adventure Time creator's latest is a delightfully weird romp through the multiverse|first=Petrana|last=Radulovic|date=March 16, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]}}</ref> These interviews are based on the real interviews derived from Trussell's podcasts interviews that were added to the show with addiction of psychedelic apocalyptic tapestry of the animation.<ref name= \"CBRIn\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbr.com/interview-duncan-trussell-midnight-gospel/|title=Midnight Gospel's Trussell Explains The Show's Intensely Personal Last Episode|first=Reuben|last=Baron|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020|website=[[CBR.com]]}}</ref>\n\n==Cast and characters==\n===Main===\n* [[Duncan Trussell]] as Clancy Gilroy\n\n===Recurring===\n* [[Phil Hendrie]] as Universe Simulator and various characters\n* [[Stephen Root]] as Bill Taft and various characters\n* [[Maria Bamford]] as Butt Demon and various characters\n* [[Doug Lussenhop]] as Daniel Hoops and various characters\n* [[Joey Diaz|Joey \"Coco\" Diaz]] as Chuck Charles and various characters\n* [[Christina Pazsitzky|Christina P.]] as Bobua and various characters\n* [[Steve Little (actor)|Steve Little]] as Captain Bryce and various characters\n* [[Johnny Pemberton]] as Cornelius and various characters\n\n===Guest stars===\n* [[Drew Pinsky]] as Little President (Episode 1 and Episode 5)\n* [[Anne Lamott]] as Anne Deer Dog (Episode 2)\n* Raghu Markas as Raghu Deer Dog (Episode 2)\n* [[Damien Echols]] as Darryl the Fish (Episode 3)\n* Trudy Goodman as Trudy the Love Barbarian (Episode 4)\n* Jason Louv as Jason (Episode 5)\n* [[David Nichtern]] as His Divine Grace, God's Scientist (Episode 1) and David (Episode 6)\n* [[Caitlin Doughty]] as Death (Episode 7)\n* Deneen Fendig as herself aka Duncan's mom and Clancy's mom (Episode 8)\n* [[Ram Dass]] as Ram Dass (Episode 8)\n\n==Episodes==\n===Season 1 (2020)===\n{{Episode table |background=#FEDA4A |overall=5 |season=5 |title=26 |director=12 |writer=35 |aux2=14 |airdate=17 |aux2T=Interview Subject(s) |released=y |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 1\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n| Title           = Taste of the King\n| DirectedBy      = Pendleton Ward\n| WrittenBy       = Mike L. Mayfield, Duncan Trussell and Pendleton Ward\n| Aux2            = [[Drew Pinsky]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|04|20}}\n| ShortSummary    = Clancy visits Earth 4-169, which happens to be in the midst of a zombie apocalypse. Clancy decides to interview the sim Glasses Man, who he discovers is, in fact, the President in this universe. In front of the White House, a group of anti-marijuana protesters are gathered, seemingly unbothered by the zombies around them. This sparks debate between Clancy and Glasses Man as to whether there is such a thing as a 'good drug' or a 'bad drug'. Over the course of the episode, the two discuss the pros and cons of psychedelics, the dangers of drug usage if not well educated, and whether or not drugs can be beneficial for an individual's personal spiritual growth. They end up helping a pregnant woman give birth before they are all turned into zombies. However, they find the new situation relieving. This does not last long as they are hit with a cure that, ironically, causes those still left as zombies to devour them. Clancy returns to his dimension as the Earth explodes.\n| LineColor       = FEDA4A\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 2\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n| Title           = Officers and Wolves\n| DirectedBy      = Pendleton Ward \n| WrittenBy       = Mike L. Mayfield, Duncan Trussell, Brendon Walsh and Pendleton Ward\n| Aux2            = [[Anne Lamott]] and Raghu Markus\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|04|20}}\n| ShortSummary    = On a planet populated by baby clowns, Clancy hears a deer-dog's thoughts on death as they head to a slaughterhouse.\n| LineColor       = FEDA4A\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 3\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n| Title           = Hunters Without a Home\n| DirectedBy      = Pendleton Ward\n| WrittenBy       = Mike L. Mayfield, Duncan Trussell and Pendleton Ward\n|Aux2             = [[Damien Echols]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|04|20}}\n| ShortSummary    = Clancy zaps to an underwater planet, where he crosses paths with Darryl, a student of ceremonial magic and the path to enlightenment. \n| LineColor       = FEDA4A\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 4\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n| Title           = Blinded by my End\n| DirectedBy      = Pendleton Ward \n| WrittenBy       = Meredith Kecskemety, Mike L. Mayfield, Duncan Trussell and Pendleton Ward\n| Aux2            = Trudy Goodman\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|04|20}}\n| ShortSummary    = A mishap sends Clancy to a medieval planet, where he rides along with a knight on a mission to avenge her lover's murder.\n| LineColor       = FEDA4A\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 5\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 5\n| Title           = Annihilation of Joy\n| DirectedBy      = Pendleton Ward \n| WrittenBy       = Mike L. Mayfield, Duncan Trussell and Pendleton Ward\n| Aux2            = Jason Louv\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|04|20}}\n| ShortSummary    = At a prison for simulated beings suffering from existential dread, Clancy ponders reality as he watches an inmate perish over and over.\n| LineColor       = FEDA4A\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 6\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 6\n| Title           = Vulture With Honor\n| DirectedBy      = Pendleton Ward \n| WrittenBy       = Mike L. Mayfield, Duncan Trussell and Pendleton Ward\n| Aux2            = [[David Nichtern]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|04|20}}\n| ShortSummary    = When his simulator malfunctions, Clancy is forced to face a few real-world problems. Later, he meets a meditation master. \n| LineColor       = FEDA4A\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 7\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 7\n| Title           = Turtles of the Eclipse\n| DirectedBy      = Pendleton Ward\n| WrittenBy       = Mike L. Mayfield, Duncan Trussell and Pendleton Ward\n| Aux2            = [[Caitlin Doughty]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|04|20}}\n| ShortSummary    = A boring trip takes a remarkable turn when Clancy accidentally falls into another world - and comes face to face with Death.\n| LineColor       = FEDA4A\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 8\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 8\n| Title           = Mouse of Silver\n| DirectedBy      = Pendleton Ward\n| WrittenBy       = Mike L. Mayfield, Duncan Trussell and Pendleton Ward\n| Aux2            = Deneen Fendig\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|04|20}}\n| ShortSummary    = Clancy joins his mother on an emotional journey through the wondrous cycle of birth, life and death.\n| LineColor       = FEDA4A\n}}\n}}\n\n==Production==\n===Concept and creation===\nDuring the start of his podcast broadcast (around 2013), Trussel received an email from Ward praising him for his podcast.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Prudom |first1=Laura |title=Netflix's The Midnight Gospel: Exclusive First Look at Adventure Time Creator's Adult Animated Series|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/netflix-the-midnight-gospel-release-date-trailer-adventure-time |website=[[IGN]] |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> About a year later, Ward left \"[[Adventure Time]]\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Strauss |first1=Neil |title=\u2018Adventure Time\u2019: The Trippiest Show on Television|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/tv-news/adventure-time-the-trippiest-show-on-television-84180/ |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |date=October 2, 2014}}</ref> Despite saying in an interview that he would not work on another series, Ward was taking the first steps in a new series anchored in the adaptation of Trussell's podcast. Some time later Trussell and Ward became friends and Ward suggested to Trussell to turn his podcast into an animated series. According to Ward, Trussell had the ability to make 2 hours of a meditation conversation funny. Trussell says: \"He reached out to me and said he had an idea for how to animate my podcast, which was another big thrill for me.\"<ref name=\"Inverse\">{{cite web |last1=Kleinman |first1=Jake |title='Midnight Gospel' Was Seven Years In The Making. Here's How It Finally Happened.|url=https://www.inverse.com/entertainment/midnight-gospel-netflix-duncan-trussell-pendleton-ward |website=[[Inverse (website)|Inverse]]|accessdate=April 20, 2020 |date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> In the first meeting with Ward, Trussell declined to join to a new project claiming he was too busy to turn his podcast into an animated show. In 2018, Ward approached to him again to show a rough concept taking a podcast conversation about drug addiction and playing it over an animatic of Trussell and his guest fighting off a zombie invasion.<ref name=\"Inverse\"/>\n\nLater, the rough of concept ended up being incorporated into the pilot of the series. The two took the concept of the series in pitching form to Mike Moon, head of adult animations at Netflix. In 2019, Netflix has ordered eight episodes, which is slated to premiere in sometime in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/netflix-order-adult-animated-series-the-midnight-gospel-from-pendleton-ward-duncan-trussell-1202814276/|title=Netflix Orders Adult Animated Series \u2018The Midnight Gospel\u2019 From Pendleton Ward & Duncan Trussell|website=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]]|first1=Denise|last1=Petski|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=December 19, 2019}}</ref> After gaining the green light, the two gathered a team of comedians like [[Johnny Pemberton]], Brendon Walsh, [[\"Weird Al\" Yankovic]] and [[Emo Philips]] were joined by occult scholar Jason Louv and white witch Maja D\u2019Aoust. The two assembled a team of approximately 190 people at Titmouse and started working on creating the episodes.<ref name=\"AnMag\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/streaming/light-at-the-end-of-the-apocalypse-pen-ward-duncan-trussell-preach-the-midnight-gospel/|title=Light at the End of the Apocalypse: Pen Ward & Duncan Trussell Preach 'The Midnight Gospel'|website=Animation Magazine|first=Ramin|last=Zahed|date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> Mike Mayfield joined the project as supervising director and writer for all the episodes. The team behind the show are composed by Jesse Moynihan (art director), Antonio Canobbio (Chief Creative Officer for Titmouse), Mike Roush (animation director) and Joey Adams (storyboard supervisor). Mayfield said that the time needed to \"try something nine different ways before one little change would make it go from clunky to incredible.\"<ref name=\"AnMag\"/>\n\nDuring the beginning of production was they need to know how much of the episodes will be story to how much will be a podcast conversation, and they also need to choose which parts of the podcast to use in the show. According to Trussell the parts of podcast who entered the series are about highlighting revelatory moments from his career. Trussell said: \u201cWhen I\u2019m doing a podcast, there are moments where my whole universe changes because someone told me something that I never knew. Once you hear that, you\u2019re forever changed; you live in a completely different dimension than you lived in before.\u201d<ref name=\"The Daily Beast\">{{cite web |last1=Schager|first1=Nick |title=From the minds of \u201cAdventure Time\u201d creator Pendleton Ward and podcaster Duncan Trussell comes this fantastically beautiful head-trip of a show. |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/the-midnight-gospel-on-netflix-is-trippy-horny-and-the-next-great-animated-show |website=[[The Daily Beast]]|accessdate=April 20, 2020 |date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> The main challenge of writing the episodes, besides choosing the best interviews, was making them coherent for animation. They also worked to find a way to embed them in psychedelic apocalyptic tapestry of the animation. The episodes should have a balance so that the animation does not take people out of the interview. With an excessive focus on animation people would not pay attention to everything at the same time. The team worked to let the conversations react with the world.<ref name=\"CBRIn\"/> According Trussell the influence for The Midnight Gospel come from [[Adult Swim]] lo-fi aesthetic in general and shows like Space Ghost: Coast 2 Coast and [[Aqua Teen Hunger Force]]. Others shows included [[Watership Down]], [[The Last Unicorn]], Liquid Television; Aeon Flux and [[David Lynch]] was a big influence in how when you watch [[Twin Peak]].<ref name=\"CBRIn\"/>\n\nFor Ward, that it was Trussell\u2019s long-form audio chats that inspired him to return to TV animation <ref name=\"The Daily Beast\"/> and the new series was a chance to explore the brave, new world of making animation for grown-ups. Until then he had made animations for children only and the new show would be a chance to change his way of making animations using the ultra-violence of cartoons with conversations on compassion. Ward also allowed Trussell to include his own original music in several episodes. The show's title came from the good news sense of the word gospel. Trussell says \"\u2019Gospel\u2019 means good news, and I was hoping that we convey the message that even through the most catastrophic situations, when everything is falling part, there is opportunity to grow as a person.\u201d<ref name=\"AnMag\"/>\n\nA second season for the show is uncertain. According to Trussell \"[the world of the Chromatic Ribbon] is a very big world. I spent a long time with Pen working out all the details. Some people might see it and think some people are saying gibberish, that somewhat was absurd and unintended, but every brick in that structure, every piece of the puzzle is intentional and based on a lot of lore. It's a very, very, very, very interesting big world, and I would love to explore that world for as long as I possibly can.\"<ref name=\"CBRIn\"/>\n\n===Marketing===\nThe first teaser was released on March 16, and the main trailer on April 6. As part of the promotional action for series, Netflix launched on April 19, 2020 on its YouTube channel a live with a countdown to series. Throughout the live, small portions of the episode were shown as well as a psychedelic animation.<ref name=\"Countdown\"/>\n\n==Release==\nThe eight-episode first season, ordered by [[Netflix]], was released on April 20, 2020. According to Trussell, the Netflix executives first suggested dropping the series on the unofficial stoner holiday and Ward suggests putting the show out on 4/20. The date is Trussell's birthday and [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]]-oriented celebrations that take place annually on April 20.<ref name=\"The Daily Beast\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|11639414}}\n\n{{Netflix original current series}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Midnight Gospel}}\n[[Category:2020 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2020s animated television series]]\n[[Category:American adult animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n[[Category:Surrealist television series]]\n[[Category:Television series by Netflix Animation]]\n[[Category:Television series created by Pendleton Ward]]\n", "name_user": "Prince Silversaddle", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor fixes.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Midnight_Gospel"}
{"title_page": "Charlie Taylor (footballer, born 1993)", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=October 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                = Charlie Taylor\n| image               = Charlie Taylor 2016.jpg\n| image_size          = 200\n| caption             = Taylor playing for [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] in 2016\n| fullname            = Charles James Taylor<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/612828 |title=Updated squads for 2017/18 Premier League confirmed |publisher=Premier League |date=2 February 2018 |accessdate=10 February 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1993|9|18|df=y}}<ref>{{Hugman|25503|accessdate=18 December 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_place         = [[York]], England\n| height              = {{convert|1.76|m|order=flip}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.burnleyfootballclub.com/teams/first-team/defender/charlie-taylor/ |title=Charlie Taylor |publisher=Burnley F.C. |accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref>\n| position            = [[Left back]]\n| currentclub         = [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]]\n| clubnumber          = 3\n| youthyears1         = {{0|0000}}\u20132011\n| youthclubs1         = [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]\n| years1              = 2011\u20132017\n| clubs1              = [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]\n| caps1               = 93\n| goals1              = 3\n| years2              = 2012\n| clubs2              = \u2192 [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] (loan)\n| caps2               = 3\n| goals2              = 0\n| years3              = 2012\n| clubs3              = \u2192 [[York City F.C.|York City]] (loan)\n| caps3               = 4\n| goals3              = 0\n| years4              = 2013\n| clubs4              = \u2192 [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]] (loan)\n| caps4               = 7\n| goals4              = 0\n| years5              = 2013\u20132014\n| clubs5              = \u2192 [[Fleetwood Town F.C.|Fleetwood Town]] (loan)\n| caps5               = 32\n| goals5              = 0\n| years6              = 2017\u2013\n| clubs6              = [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]]\n| caps6               = 66\n| goals6              = 0\n| nationalyears1      = 2011\n| nationalteam1       = [[England national under-19 football team|England U19]]\n| nationalcaps1       = 2\n| nationalgoals1      = 0\n| club-update         = 09:47, 8 March 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = \n}}\n'''Charles James Taylor''' (born 18 September 1993) is an English professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[left back]] for {{English football updater|Burnley}} club [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]]. He is a former [[England national under-19 football team|England U19]] international.\n\n==Club career==\n===Early career===\nBorn in [[York]], North Yorkshire,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/players/charlie-taylor-238146/ |title=Charlie Taylor |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=10 February 2018}}</ref> Taylor attended [[Tadcaster Grammar School]] and played in the junior teams at [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] before signing as a scholar with the club upon leaving school in the summer of 2010.<ref name=\"Charlie Taylor signs Leeds United contract\">{{cite news\n| title = Charlie Taylor signs Leeds United contract\n| url = http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/sport/9058849.Acaster_Malbis_footballer_signs_Leeds_United_contract/\n| newspaper = The Press\n| location = York\n| date = 1 June 2011\n| accessdate = 26 August 2012}}</ref> During his first year in the youth team, Taylor was a regular for the under-18s, and in the second half of the [[2010\u201311 Leeds United F.C. season|2010\u201311]] season established himself in the reserve team, featuring in nine matches.<ref name=\"Charlie Taylor signs Leeds United contract\"/> While playing for the under-18s against [[Newcastle United F.C. Reserves and Academy|Newcastle United]] he scored a goal which would be awarded the LFE's 2010\u201311 Academy & Youth Alliance Goal of the Season in April 2011, with LFE chief executive Alan Sykes describing it as an \"incredible strike\".<ref name=\"Charlie wins Goal of the Season\">{{Cite web\n| title = Charlie wins Goal of the Season\n| url = http://www.leedsunited.com/news/20110616/charlie-wins-goal-of-the-season_2247585_2377227\n| publisher = Leeds United F.C.\n| date = 16 June 2011\n| accessdate = 11 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe capped his first year as a scholar by turning professional after signing a three-year contract at the club in May 2011.<ref name=\"Academy youngster earns pro deal\">{{Cite web\n| title = Academy youngster earns pro deal\n| url = http://www.leedsunited.com/news/20110523/academy-youngster-earns-pro-deal_2247585_2365303\n| publisher = Leeds United F.C.\n| date = 23 May 2011\n| accessdate = 11 March 2012}}</ref> The length of the contract reflected the club's value of the player with fellow youngsters [[Alex Cairns]] and twins Lewis and Nathan Turner earning only one-year deals initially.<ref name=\"Academy trio offered pro deals\">{{Cite web\n| title = Academy trio offered pro deals\n| url = http://www.leedsunited.com/news/20110509/academy-trio-offered-pro-deals_2247585_2356388\n| publisher = Leeds United F.C.\n| date = 9 May 2011\n| accessdate = 30 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Senior debut and loan moves===\nAt 17 years of age, Taylor made his first-team debut for Leeds as a second half [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] against local rivals [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] in the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]] on 9 August 2011.<ref name=\"Nunez double seals Cup progress\">{{Cite web\n| title = Nunez double seals Cup progress\n| url = http://www.leedsunited.com/news/20110809/nunez-double-seals-cup-progress_2247585_2415087\n| publisher = Leeds United F.C.\n| date = 9 August 2011\n| accessdate = 11 March 2012}}</ref> He made his [[EFL Championship|Championship]] debut for Leeds at left back on 10 September against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]], replacing the suspended [[Aidy White]].<ref name=\"McCormack seals United victory\">{{Cite web\n| title = McCormack seals United victory\n| url = http://www.leedsunited.com/news/20110910/mccormack-seals-united-victory_2247585_2446651\n| publisher = Leeds United F.C.\n| date = 10 September 2011\n| accessdate = 30 August 2012}}</ref> He gained an assist for [[Ross McCormack]]'s goal who scored the opener of the match in Leeds' 3\u20132 victory.<ref name=\"McCormack seals United victory\"/> Despite a promising debut, Taylor was dropped for the following match against [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] with White coming back into the team.<ref name=\"Late winner secures United success\">{{Cite web\n| title = Late winner secures United success\n| url = http://www.leedsunited.com/news/20110917/late-winner-secures-united-success_2247585_2453860\n| publisher = Leeds United F.C.\n| date = 17 September 2011\n| accessdate = 30 August 2012}}</ref> Taylor was named as an unused substitute in the 3\u20130 loss against rivals [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in the League Cup on 20 September 2011.<ref name=\"United slip out of Cup\">{{Cite web\n| title = United slip out of Cup\n| url = http://www.leedsunited.com/news/20110920/united-slip-out-of-cup_2247585_2457062\n| publisher = Leeds United F.C.\n| date = 20 September 2011\n| accessdate = 30 August 2012}}</ref> His appearances in the senior team would lead Taylor to being called up to the [[England national under-19 football team|England under-19]] squad the following month for the Limoges Tournament.<ref name=\"England Vs Ukraine\">{{Cite web\n| title = England Vs Ukraine\n| url = http://www.thefa.com/England/mens-u19s/News/Match%20Centre/UkrainevEngland/england-u19s-3-1-ukraine-report\n| publisher = The Football Association\n| date = 10 October 2011\n| accessdate = 10 October 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"LUFC Leeds youngster helps England win tournament\">{{cite news\n| title = LUFC Leeds youngster helps England win tournament\n| url = http://www.leeds.vitalfootball.co.uk/article.asp?a=258324\n| work=Vital Leeds |publisher=Vital Network\n| date = 10 October 2011\n| accessdate=16 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nTaylor joined [[EFL League Two|League Two]] outfit Bradford City on an initial one-month [[Loan (sports)|loan]] on 1 January 2012 in order to gain further first-team experience.<ref name=\"Leeds youngster joins Bradford City on loan\">{{Cite news\n| first = Simon\n| last = Parker\n| title = Leeds youngster joins Bradford City on loan\n| url = http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/sportbcfc/9446408.Leeds_youngster_joins_Bradford_City_on_loan/\n| newspaper = Telegraph & Argus\n| location = Bradford\n| date = 1 January 2012\n| accessdate = 30 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Taylor joins Bantams on loan\">{{Cite web\n| title = Taylor joins Bantams on loan\n| url = http://www.leedsunited.com/news/20120101/taylor-joins-bantams-on-loan_2247585_2562869\n| publisher = Leeds United F.C.\n| date = 1 January 2012\n| accessdate = 1 January 2012}}</ref> Bradford decided against extending the loan after it expired, having made four appearances.<ref name=\"Taylor returns to Leeds\">{{Cite news\n| title = Taylor returns to Leeds\n| url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11715/7467686/Taylor-returns-to-Leeds\n| publisher = Sky Sports\n| date = 31 January 2012\n| accessdate = 8 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nTaylor joined hometown club [[York City F.C.|York City]], who were newly [[Promotion and relegation|promoted]] to League Two, on an initial one-month loan on 30 August 2012.<ref name=\"Clarke Carlisle, Scott Dobie and Charlie Taylor join York City\">{{Cite news\n| title = Clarke Carlisle, Scott Dobie and Charlie Taylor join York City\n| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19421919\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 30 August 2012\n| accessdate = 30 August 2012}}</ref> He made his debut two days later in a 3\u20131 home victory over [[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford United]].<ref name=sb1213/> Despite being second to [[Jamal Fyfield]] in the left-back pecking order, the loan was extended for a second month on 28 September 2012.<ref name=\"Scott Dobie released by York City\">{{Cite news\n| first = Dave\n| last = Flett\n| title = Scott Dobie released by York City\n| url = http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/sport/9956023.Scott_Dobie_released_by_York_City/\n| newspaper = The Press\n| location = York\n| date = 28 September 2012\n| accessdate = 4 November 2013}}</ref> Having made five appearances for York, Taylor returned to Leeds on 26 October 2012, shortly before the expiration of the loan.<ref name=sb1213/><ref name=\"Mills: Lee Bullock's York City career not over\">{{Cite news\n| first = Dave\n| last = Flett\n| title = Mills: Lee Bullock's York City career not over\n| url = http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/sport/10010056.Mills__Lee_Bullock___s_York_City_career_not_over/\n| newspaper = The Press\n| location = York\n| date = 26 October 2012\n| accessdate = 4 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe joined [[Scottish Premier League]] club [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]] on loan until the end of the [[2012\u201313 Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C. season|2012\u201313]] season on 25 January 2013.<ref name=\"Inverness CT land Leeds defender Charlie Taylor on loan\">{{Cite news\n| title = Inverness CT land Leeds defender Charlie Taylor on loan\n| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21194175\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 25 January 2013\n| accessdate = 25 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Fleetwood Town (loan)====\n[[File:Charlie Taylor 26-10-2013 1.jpg|thumb|upright|Taylor playing for [[Fleetwood Town F.C.|Fleetwood Town]] in 2013]]\n\nOn 18 October 2013, Taylor joined [[Fleetwood Town F.C.|Fleetwood Town]] on a one-month loan after being signed by manager [[Graham Alexander]].<ref name=\"Taylor strengthens defence\">{{Cite web\n| title = Taylor strengthens defence\n| url = http://www.fleetwoodtownfc.com/news/article/taylor-strengthens-defence-1115634.aspx\n| publisher = Fleetwood Town F.C.\n| date = 18 October 2013\n| accessdate = 18 October 2013}}</ref> Taylor made his debut for Fleetwood Town on the same day, playing in a 2\u20130 defeat against [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]].<ref name=\"Southend 2 Fleetwood 0\">{{Cite news\n| title = Southend 2 Fleetwood 0\n| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24486575\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 18 October 2013\n| accessdate = 18 October 2013}}</ref> After impressing in his first month at the club, on 6 November, Taylor's loan was extended until January 2014.<ref name=\"Leeds United's Charlie Taylor extends Fleetwood Town loan deal\">{{Cite news\n| title = Leeds United's Charlie Taylor extends Fleetwood Town loan deal\n| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24837110\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 6 November 2013\n| accessdate = 6 November 2013}}</ref> After extending Taylor's loan, manager Graham Alexander announced his delight in being able to keep Taylor,<ref name=\"Grezza delighted to keep Charlie at Town\">{{Cite news\n| title = Grezza delighted to keep Charlie at Town\n| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/sport/fleetwood-town/grezza-delighted-to-keep-charlie-at-town-1-6221945\n|newspaper=Blackpool Gazette\n| date = 7 November 2013\n| accessdate = 7 November 2013}}</ref> with Taylor earning rave reviews for his performances.<ref name=\"Young Charlie's been the talk of the Town\">{{cite news\n| title = Young Charlie's been the talk of the Town\n| url = http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/latest-whites-news/leeds-united-young-charlie-s-been-the-talk-of-the-town-1-6221728\n|newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |location=Leeds\n| date = 7 November 2013\n| accessdate = 7 November 2013}}</ref> On 17 December, his loan was extended to the end of the season.<ref name=\"Taylor extends Fleetwood stay\">{{Cite news\n| title = Taylor extends Fleetwood stay\n| url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11065/9078006/taylor-extends-fleetwood-stay\n| publisher = Sky Sports\n| date = 17 December 2013\n| accessdate = 17 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nTaylor's form helped Fleetwood Town qualify for the play-off's with a fourth-placed finish in League Two. Fleetwood Town semi-final opponents were Taylor's old club [[York City F.C.|York City]], with Taylor revealing in an interview on 10 May that he wanted to prove people wrong at his former club.<ref name=\"Taylor ready to face hometown club\">{{Cite web\n| title = Taylor ready to face hometown club\n| url = http://www.fleetwoodtownfc.com/news/article/taylor-ready-to-face-hometown-club-1543713.aspx\n| publisher = Fleetwood Town F.C.\n| date = 10 May 2014\n| accessdate = 10 May 2014}}</ref> On 13 May, it was reported that Taylor had impressed new Leeds United owner [[Massimo Cellino]] who was looking at offering Taylor an extended three-year contract, with Taylor's current contract due to expire.<ref name=\"Leeds United: Charlie Taylor set to land new contract\">{{cite news\n| title = Leeds United: Charlie Taylor set to land new contract\n| url = http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/latest-whites-news/leeds-united-charlie-taylor-set-to-land-new-contract-1-6614671\n|newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |location=Leeds\n| date = 13 May 2014\n| accessdate = 13 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter helping guide Fleetwood Town to the League Two play-off's final against [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]], on 20 May Taylor signed a three-year contract extension at his parent club Leeds United. The deal would keep Taylor at the club until 2017.<ref name=\"CHARLIE SIGNS UP\">{{Cite web\n| title = CHARLIE SIGNS UP\n| url = http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/16rgx4lk8mo781m082hn7gx1l6/title/charlie-signs-up\n| publisher = Leeds United F.C.\n| date = 20 May 2014\n| accessdate = 20 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 May, Taylor started the League Two play-off final against Burton Albion. Fleetwood gained promotion with a 1\u20130 victory after a goal from Taylor's teammate [[Antoni Sarcevic]].<ref>{{Cite news\n| title = Burton 0 \u2013 Fleetwood 1 : League 2 Playoff Final\n| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27465323\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 26 May 2014\n| accessdate = 26 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Leeds return===\n====2014\u201315 season====\nOn 1 August, Taylor was assigned the number 21 shirt for the 2014\u201315 season.<ref name=\"SQUAD NUMBERS RELEASED\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/1wncxa2kw0zr11fmlyjr0m3t53/title/squad-numbers-released|title=Squad Numbers Released|publisher=Leeds United F.C.|date=1 August 2014 |accessdate=1 August 2014}}</ref> Taylor made his first start for Leeds since returning from loan on 12 August 2014, starting the League Cup match against [[Accrington Stanley F.C.|Accrington Stanley]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Leeds V Accrington|url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/17zjc7q85j4pm1c43n56bi1r92/title/accrington-live!|publisher=Leeds United F.C.|accessdate=12 August 2014|date=12 August 2014}}</ref> Taylor replaced [[Stephen Warnock]] in Leeds' 1\u20130 victory against [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] on 30 August.<ref>{{cite web |title=Leeds Vs Bolton Wanderers|date=30 August 2014|accessdate=30 August 2014|url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/3fqrhs11d9xa18kq62h7zlkrz/title/bolton-live!|publisher=Leeds United F.C.}}</ref>\n\nAfter the then captain Stephen Warnock suffered an injury in a league match against [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] on 30 December 2014, Taylor came back into the starting lineup on 4 January 2015 in Leeds' [[FA Cup]] 1\u20130 defeat against [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/329650/report|title=Sunderland 1 Leeds 0| date=4 January 2015|accessdate=4 January 2015|publisher=Sky Sports}}</ref> The form of Taylor coming into the team saw regular left back Warnock sold to Derby.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/latest-whites-news/leeds-united-defender-cooper-looks-set-to-be-whites-new-captain-1-7053911|title=Leeds United: Defender Cooper looks set to be Whites' new captain| date=15 January 2015|accessdate=15 January 2015|newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |location=Leeds}}</ref>\n\nAfter impressing at left back, Taylor was played as a left winger for Leeds under Coach [[Neil Redfearn]] as part of a new 4\u20132\u20133\u20131 formation, with [[Gaetano Berardi]] filling in the left back slot. Taylor scored his first goal for Leeds in a 4\u20133 loss against [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Dave Edwards headed home a late winner as Wolves beat Leeds|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32111079 |date=6 April 2015 |accessdate=6 April 2015 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April, after rumoured Premier League interest in Taylor and teammates [[Lewis Cook (footballer, born 1997)|Lewis Cook]], [[Alex Mowatt]] and [[Sam Byram]], head coach [[Neil Redfearn]] challenged Leeds United's owners to keep a hold of their home grown talents.<ref>{{cite news |title=Keep young stars, Redfearn challenges Leeds |url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/latest-whites-news/leeds-united-keep-young-stars-redfearn-challenges-leeds-1-7202015 |date=9 April 2015 |accessdate=9 April 2015 |newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |location=Leeds |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150415180425/http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/latest-whites-news/leeds-united-keep-young-stars-redfearn-challenges-leeds-1-7202015 |archive-date=15 April 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nTaylor scored his second goal for the club on 25 April in a 2\u20131 win against Yorkshire rivals [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Sheffield Wednesday 1\u20132 Leeds United|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32362055 |date=25 April 2015 |accessdate=26 April 2015 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 2 May 2015, Taylor was also nominated for Young Player of the Year Award, but missed out to Lewis Cook.<ref>{{cite web |title= Mowatt Scoops Awards Night Double |date=2 May 2015|url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/slzwndu1a9wb1kdweft4sskxz/title/mowatt-scoops-awards-night-double|publisher=Leeds United F.C.}}</ref>\n\n====2015\u201316 season====\n[[File:Charlie Taylor 1993.jpg|thumb|upright|Taylor celebrating a goal for [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] in 2015]]\n\nOn 19 September 2015, Taylor scored the winner for Leeds against [[Milton Keynes Dons F.C.|Milton Keynes Dons]] in a 2\u20131 victory, with an impressive solo goal running from his own half before scoring a left footed shot.<ref>{{cite news|title= MK Dons 1\u20132 Leeds: Chris Wood and Charlie Taylor goals enough for victory|date=19 September 2015|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/mk-dons-vs-leeds/339622|publisher=Sky Sports}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 April, Taylor was nominated for the Leeds United player of the year award, alongside [[Mirco Antenucci]], [[Liam Bridcutt]], [[Gaetano Berardi]] and [[Lewis Cook (footballer, born 1997)|Lewis Cook]].<ref>{{cite web | title= Player of the Year: Top 5 Vote!| url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/168ovfdrck3da1m2zselrih16n/title/player-of-the-year-top-5-vote! |publisher= Leeds United F.C. | date= 19 April 2016 | accessdate= 19 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 April 2016, at the club's annual Player of the Year Awards, Taylor was named The Fans Player of the Year for the 2015\u201316 season. On the same day Taylor also won the ''[[Yorkshire Evening Post]]''{{'}}s Player of the Year Award.<ref name=POTY>{{cite web |title=Taylor crowned Player of the Year |url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/41r05ixj1r961pyc64yxluocb/title/taylor-crowned-player-of-the-year |publisher=Leeds United F.C. |date=30 April 2016 |accessdate=2 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter being linked with several [[Premier League]] clubs including [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] and [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]], on 15 June 2016, Leeds owner [[Massimo Cellino]] revealed he had approached Taylor's agent about extending Taylors contract, however he said upon a possible contract extension ''Charlie is going to be a problem, I think his agent is the same as [[Sam Byram]]. Taylor doesn't return the call''.<ref>{{cite news | title= Leeds confident of securing Bournemouth target Lewis Cook on fresh terms&nbsp;... but fear Charlie Taylor will not sign a new deal| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-3643473/Leeds-confident-securing-Bournemouth-target-Lewis-Cook-fresh-terms-fear-Charlie-Taylor-not-sign-new-deal.html |newspaper= Daily Mail |location=London | date= 15 June 2016 | accessdate= 15 June 2016}}{{Unreliable source?|date=October 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2016\u201317 season====\nOn 2 August 2016, with speculation still linking Taylor with a move to the Premier League, Leeds announced they had rejected a transfer request from Taylor to leave the club, with the club advising that chairman [[Massimo Cellino]] had said Taylor would not be sold.<ref>{{cite web | title= Club Statement: Charlie Taylor| url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/2nuz0hb14ylq1cb1bw1p0162c |publisher= Leeds United F.C. | date= 2 August 2016 | accessdate= 2 August 2016}}</ref> On 22 August, after Leeds's 2\u20130 victory against [[Sheffield Wednesday]] Taylor proclaimed ''I am contracted until the end of this season, so if they (Leeds) do not want to sell me, then I am under contract. It is up to them and their decision and if they keep me, then I will be until then.''<ref>{{cite news | title= Leeds United: Charlie Taylor keen for future to be resolved as Premier League trio eye classy defender| url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-charlie-taylor-keen-for-future-to-be-resolved-as-premier-league-trio-eye-classy-defender-1-8081598 |newspaper= Yorkshire Evening Post |location=Leeds | date= 22 August 2016 | accessdate= 22 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nTaylor stayed at the club, and despite speculation on his long-term future at the club, Taylor was an impressive performer as his performances at Left-back helped Leeds reach 5th place and a playoff position at Christmas 2016.<ref>{{cite news | title= Leeds starlet Charlie Taylor could be the next academy product to follow Sam Byram out of Elland Road| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-4060036/Leeds-starlet-Charlie-Taylor-academy-product-leave-Elland-Road.html |newspaper= Daily Mail |location=London | date= 22 December 2016 | accessdate= 23 December 2016}}{{Unreliable source?|date=October 2017}}</ref> On 29 December 2016, Taylor missed his first Leeds match after 52 consecutive starts, in the match against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in a 1\u20131 draw after picking up an achilles injury against [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] in the previous match.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/match-reports/aston-villa-1-leeds-united-12383620|title=Aston Villa 1 Leeds 1 |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=29 December 2016|accessdate=29 December 2016}}</ref> The injury would keep Taylor out for several months, also added to the form of Left-back [[Gaetano Berardi]], Taylor was unable to reclaim his place in the team.\n\nIn the final match of the season with Leeds missing out on the play-offs bar an almost impossible mathematical goal difference swing, it was revealed by Head coach [[Garry Monk]] that Taylor had refused to play for Leeds in the final match. As a result of the refusal, Taylor was fined two weeks wages by the club with Monk proclaiming \"I'm hugely disappointed with Charlie. I think he's been terribly advised all season.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39844095|title=Charlie Taylor: Leeds boss Garry Monk unhappy after defender misses Wigan game|publisher=BBC Sport|date=8 May 2017|accessdate=8 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 May 2017, it was announced that Taylor had been offered a 2-year contract with the club in line with EFL regulations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/21895/2017-18-retained-list|title=2017/18 Retained List|publisher=Leeds United F.C. |date=17 May 2017|accessdate=17 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Burnley===\nOn 6 July 2017, Taylor signed a four-year contract with Premier League club [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]]. Since Taylor was under 24, Burnley owed Leeds United compensation, which was due to be set at a [[Tribunals in the United Kingdom|tribunal]].<ref>{{cite web|date=6 July 2017|accessdate=6 July 2017|url=https://www.burnleyfootballclub.com/news/2017/july/taylor-raring-to-go-following-turf-move/|publisher=Burnley F.C.|title=Taylor Raring To Go Following Turf Move}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=6 July 2017|accessdate=6 July 2017|url=https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/22023/club-statement-charlie-taylor|publisher=Leeds United F.C.|title=Club Statement: Charlie Taylor}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/charlie-taylor-completes-his-move-from-leeds-united-to-burnley-1-8634575 |title=Charlie Taylor completes his move from Leeds United to Burnley |newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |location=Leeds |date=6 July 2017|accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref> On 25 July 2017, it was reported by the ''Yorkshire Evening Post'' that the clubs had agreed on a compensation of between \u00a36&nbsp;million and \u00a37&nbsp;million to be paid by Burnley to Leeds United for the player, avoiding the need for a tribunal decision.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-whites-agree-fee-with-burnley-over-taylor-move-1-8668936|title=Leeds United: Whites agree fee with Burnley over Taylor move|newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |location=Leeds |accessdate=15 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nIn October 2011, Taylor made his debut for the England under-19 team, playing in two of the three matches in the Limoges Tournament to help England earn a win in the overall tournament.<ref name=\"LUFC Leeds youngster helps England win tournament\"/> His debut came as a substitute against [[Portugal national under-19 football team|Portugal]], before starting against [[Ukraine national under-19 football team|Ukraine]].<ref name=\"LUFC Leeds youngster helps England win tournament\"/>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|match played 7 March 2020}}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|National Cup{{efn|Includes [[FA Cup]], [[Scottish Cup]]}}\n!colspan=2|League Cup{{efn|Includes [[EFL Cup|EFL Cup/League Cup]]}}\n!colspan=2|Other\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=7|[[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]\n|[[2011\u201312 Leeds United F.C. season|2011\u201312]]<ref name=sb1112>{{soccerbase season|61245|2011|accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref>\n|[[EFL Championship|Championship]]\n|2||0||0||0||2||0||colspan=2|\u2014||4||0\n|-\n|[[2012\u201313 Leeds United F.C. season|2012\u201313]]<ref name=sb1213>{{soccerbase season|61245|2012|accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref>\n|Championship\n|0||0||0||0||0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||0||0\n|-\n|[[2013\u201314 Leeds United F.C. season|2013\u201314]]<ref name=sb1314>{{soccerbase season|61245|2013|accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref>\n|Championship\n|0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||0||0\n|-\n|[[2014\u201315 Leeds United F.C. season|2014\u201315]]<ref name=sb1415>{{soccerbase season|61245|2014|accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref>\n|Championship\n|23||2||1||0||1||0||colspan=2|\u2014||25||2\n|-\n|[[2015\u201316 Leeds United F.C. season|2015\u201316]]<ref name=sb1516>{{soccerbase season|61245|2015|accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref>\n|Championship\n|39||1||3||0||1||0||colspan=2|\u2014||43||1\n|-\n|[[2016\u201317 Leeds United F.C. season|2016\u201317]]<ref name=sb1617>{{soccerbase season|61245|2016|accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref>\n|Championship\n|29||0||0||0||3||0||colspan=2|\u2014||32||0\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!93||3||4||0||7||0||colspan=2|\u2014||104||3\n|-\n|[[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] (loan)\n|[[2011\u201312 Bradford City A.F.C. season|2011\u201312]]<ref name=sb1112/>\n|[[EFL League Two|League Two]]\n|3||0||1||0||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||4||0\n|-\n|[[York City F.C.|York City]] (loan)\n|[[2012\u201313 York City F.C. season|2012\u201313]]<ref name=sb1213/>\n|League Two\n|4||0||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||1{{efn|Appearance in [[Football League Trophy]]}}||0||5||0\n|-\n|[[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]] (loan)\n|[[2012\u201313 Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C. season|2012\u201313]]<ref name=sb1213/>\n|[[Scottish Premier League]]\n|7||0||1||0||0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||8||0\n|-\n|[[Fleetwood Town F.C.|Fleetwood Town]] (loan)\n|[[2013\u201314 Fleetwood Town F.C. season|2013\u201314]]<ref name=sb1314/>\n|League Two\n|32||0||3||0||colspan=2|\u2014||7{{efn|Four appearances in Football League Trophy, three in [[EFL League Two play-offs|League Two play-offs]]}}||0||42||0\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]]\n|[[2017\u201318 Burnley F.C. season|2017\u201318]]<ref name=sb1718>{{soccerbase season|61245|2017|accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref>\n|[[Premier League]]\n|11||0||1||0||2||0||colspan=2|\u2014||14||0\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Burnley F.C. season|2018\u201319]]<ref name=sb1819>{{soccerbase season|61245|2018|accessdate=19 March 2019}}</ref>\n|Premier League\n|38||0||2||0||0||0||5{{efn|Appearances in [[UEFA Europa League]]}}||0||45||0\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 Burnley F.C. season|2019\u201320]]<ref name=sb1920>{{soccerbase season|61245|2019|accessdate=19 August 2019}}</ref>\n|Premier League\n|17||0||1||0||1||0||colspan=2|\u2014||19||0\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!66||0||4||0||3||0||5||0||78||0\n|-\n!colspan=3|Career total\n!205||3||13||0||10||0||13||0||241||3\n|}\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Fleetwood Town'''\n*[[Football League Two play-offs]]: [[2014 Football League play-offs#League Two|2014]]<ref name=sb1314/>\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] Player of the Year: [[2015\u201316 Leeds United F.C. season|2015\u201316]]<ref name=POTY/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[https://www.burnleyfootballclub.com/teams/first-team/defender/charlie-taylor/ Profile] at the Burnley F.C. website\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{Leeds United F.C. Player of the Year}}\n{{Burnley F.C. squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taylor, Charlie}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from York]]\n[[Category:Footballers from North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:England youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Leeds United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:York City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Fleetwood Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Burnley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=October 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                = Charlie Taylor\n| image               = Charlie Taylor 2016.jpg\n| image_size          = 200\n| caption             = Taylor playing for [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] in 2016\n| fullname            = Charles James Taylor<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/612828 |title=Updated squads for 2017/18 Premier League confirmed |publisher=Premier League |date=2 February 2018 |accessdate=10 February 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1993|9|18|df=y}}<ref>{{Hugman|25503|accessdate=18 December 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_place         = [[York]], England\n| height              = {{convert|1.76|m|order=flip}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.burnleyfootballclub.com/teams/first-team/defender/charlie-taylor/ |title=Charlie Taylor |publisher=Burnley F.C. |accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref>\n| position            = [[Left back]]\n| currentclub         = [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]]\n| clubnumber          = 3\n| youthyears1         = {{0|0000}}\u20132011\n| youthclubs1         = [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]\n| years1              = 2011\u20132017\n| clubs1              = [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]\n| caps1               = 93\n| goals1              = 3\n| years2              = 2012\n| clubs2              = \u2192 [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] (loan)\n| caps2               = 3\n| goals2              = 0\n| years3              = 2012\n| clubs3              = \u2192 [[York City F.C.|York City]] (loan)\n| caps3               = 4\n| goals3              = 0\n| years4              = 2013\n| clubs4              = \u2192 [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]] (loan)\n| caps4               = 7\n| goals4              = 0\n| years5              = 2013\u20132014\n| clubs5              = \u2192 [[Fleetwood Town F.C.|Fleetwood Town]] (loan)\n| caps5               = 32\n| goals5              = 0\n| years6              = 2017\u2013\n| clubs6              = [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]]\n| caps6               = 66\n| goals6              = 0\n| nationalyears1      = 2011\n| nationalteam1       = [[England national under-19 football team|England U19]]\n| nationalcaps1       = 2\n| nationalgoals1      = 0\n| club-update         = 09:47, 8 March 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = \n}}\n'''Charles James Taylor''' (born 18 September 1993) is an English professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[left back]] for {{English football updater|Burnley}} club [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]]. He is a former [[England national under-19 football team|England U19]] international.\n\n==Club career==\n===Early career===\nBorn in [[York]], North Yorkshire,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/players/charlie-taylor-238146/ |title=Charlie Taylor |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=10 February 2018}}</ref> Taylor attended [[Tadcaster Grammar School]] and played in the junior teams at [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] before signing as a scholar with the club upon leaving school in the summer of 2010.<ref name=\"Charlie Taylor signs Leeds United contract\">{{cite news\n| title = Charlie Taylor signs Leeds United contract\n| url = http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/sport/9058849.Acaster_Malbis_footballer_signs_Leeds_United_contract/\n| newspaper = The Press\n| location = York\n| date = 1 June 2011\n| accessdate = 26 August 2012}}</ref> During his first year in the youth team, Taylor was a regular for the under-18s, and in the second half of the [[2010\u201311 Leeds United F.C. season|2010\u201311]] season established himself in the reserve team, featuring in nine matches.<ref name=\"Charlie Taylor signs Leeds United contract\"/> While playing for the under-18s against [[Newcastle United F.C. Reserves and Academy|Newcastle United]] he scored a goal which would be awarded the LFE's 2010\u201311 Academy & Youth Alliance Goal of the Season in April 2011, with LFE chief executive Alan Sykes describing it as an \"incredible strike\".<ref name=\"Charlie wins Goal of the Season\">{{Cite web\n| title = Charlie wins Goal of the Season\n| url = http://www.leedsunited.com/news/20110616/charlie-wins-goal-of-the-season_2247585_2377227\n| publisher = Leeds United F.C.\n| date = 16 June 2011\n| accessdate = 11 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe capped his first year as a scholar by turning professional after signing a three-year contract at the club in May 2011.<ref name=\"Academy youngster earns pro deal\">{{Cite web\n| title = Academy youngster earns pro deal\n| url = http://www.leedsunited.com/news/20110523/academy-youngster-earns-pro-deal_2247585_2365303\n| publisher = Leeds United F.C.\n| date = 23 May 2011\n| accessdate = 11 March 2012}}</ref> The length of the contract reflected the club's value of the player with fellow youngsters [[Alex Cairns]] and twins Lewis and Nathan Turner earning only one-year deals initially.<ref name=\"Academy trio offered pro deals\">{{Cite web\n| title = Academy trio offered pro deals\n| url = http://www.leedsunited.com/news/20110509/academy-trio-offered-pro-deals_2247585_2356388\n| publisher = Leeds United F.C.\n| date = 9 May 2011\n| accessdate = 30 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Senior debut and loan moves===\nAt 17 years of age, Taylor made his first-team debut for Leeds as a second half [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] against local rivals [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] in the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]] on 9 August 2011.<ref name=\"Nunez double seals Cup progress\">{{Cite web\n| title = Nunez double seals Cup progress\n| url = http://www.leedsunited.com/news/20110809/nunez-double-seals-cup-progress_2247585_2415087\n| publisher = Leeds United F.C.\n| date = 9 August 2011\n| accessdate = 11 March 2012}}</ref> He made his [[EFL Championship|Championship]] debut for Leeds at left back on 10 September against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]], replacing the suspended [[Aidy White]].<ref name=\"McCormack seals United victory\">{{Cite web\n| title = McCormack seals United victory\n| url = http://www.leedsunited.com/news/20110910/mccormack-seals-united-victory_2247585_2446651\n| publisher = Leeds United F.C.\n| date = 10 September 2011\n| accessdate = 30 August 2012}}</ref> He gained an assist for [[Ross McCormack]]'s goal who scored the opener of the match in Leeds' 3\u20132 victory.<ref name=\"McCormack seals United victory\"/> Despite a promising debut, Taylor was dropped for the following match against [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] with White coming back into the team.<ref name=\"Late winner secures United success\">{{Cite web\n| title = Late winner secures United success\n| url = http://www.leedsunited.com/news/20110917/late-winner-secures-united-success_2247585_2453860\n| publisher = Leeds United F.C.\n| date = 17 September 2011\n| accessdate = 30 August 2012}}</ref> Taylor was named as an unused substitute in the 3\u20130 loss against rivals [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in the League Cup on 20 September 2011.<ref name=\"United slip out of Cup\">{{Cite web\n| title = United slip out of Cup\n| url = http://www.leedsunited.com/news/20110920/united-slip-out-of-cup_2247585_2457062\n| publisher = Leeds United F.C.\n| date = 20 September 2011\n| accessdate = 30 August 2012}}</ref> His appearances in the senior team would lead Taylor to being called up to the [[England national under-19 football team|England under-19]] squad the following month for the Limoges Tournament.<ref name=\"England Vs Ukraine\">{{Cite web\n| title = England Vs Ukraine\n| url = http://www.thefa.com/England/mens-u19s/News/Match%20Centre/UkrainevEngland/england-u19s-3-1-ukraine-report\n| publisher = The Football Association\n| date = 10 October 2011\n| accessdate = 10 October 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"LUFC Leeds youngster helps England win tournament\">{{cite news\n| title = LUFC Leeds youngster helps England win tournament\n| url = http://www.leeds.vitalfootball.co.uk/article.asp?a=258324\n| work=Vital Leeds |publisher=Vital Network\n| date = 10 October 2011\n| accessdate=16 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nTaylor joined [[EFL League Two|League Two]] outfit Bradford City on an initial one-month [[Loan (sports)|loan]] on 1 January 2012 in order to gain further first-team experience.<ref name=\"Leeds youngster joins Bradford City on loan\">{{Cite news\n| first = Simon\n| last = Parker\n| title = Leeds youngster joins Bradford City on loan\n| url = http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/sportbcfc/9446408.Leeds_youngster_joins_Bradford_City_on_loan/\n| newspaper = Telegraph & Argus\n| location = Bradford\n| date = 1 January 2012\n| accessdate = 30 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Taylor joins Bantams on loan\">{{Cite web\n| title = Taylor joins Bantams on loan\n| url = http://www.leedsunited.com/news/20120101/taylor-joins-bantams-on-loan_2247585_2562869\n| publisher = Leeds United F.C.\n| date = 1 January 2012\n| accessdate = 1 January 2012}}</ref> Bradford decided against extending the loan after it expired, having made four appearances.<ref name=\"Taylor returns to Leeds\">{{Cite news\n| title = Taylor returns to Leeds\n| url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11715/7467686/Taylor-returns-to-Leeds\n| publisher = Sky Sports\n| date = 31 January 2012\n| accessdate = 8 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nTaylor joined hometown club [[York City F.C.|York City]], who were newly [[Promotion and relegation|promoted]] to League Two, on an initial one-month loan on 30 August 2012.<ref name=\"Clarke Carlisle, Scott Dobie and Charlie Taylor join York City\">{{Cite news\n| title = Clarke Carlisle, Scott Dobie and Charlie Taylor join York City\n| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19421919\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 30 August 2012\n| accessdate = 30 August 2012}}</ref> He made his debut two days later in a 3\u20131 home victory over [[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford United]].<ref name=sb1213/> Despite being second to [[Jamal Fyfield]] in the left-back pecking order, the loan was extended for a second month on 28 September 2012.<ref name=\"Scott Dobie released by York City\">{{Cite news\n| first = Dave\n| last = Flett\n| title = Scott Dobie released by York City\n| url = http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/sport/9956023.Scott_Dobie_released_by_York_City/\n| newspaper = The Press\n| location = York\n| date = 28 September 2012\n| accessdate = 4 November 2013}}</ref> Having made five appearances for York, Taylor returned to Leeds on 26 October 2012, shortly before the expiration of the loan.<ref name=sb1213/><ref name=\"Mills: Lee Bullock's York City career not over\">{{Cite news\n| first = Dave\n| last = Flett\n| title = Mills: Lee Bullock's York City career not over\n| url = http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/sport/10010056.Mills__Lee_Bullock___s_York_City_career_not_over/\n| newspaper = The Press\n| location = York\n| date = 26 October 2012\n| accessdate = 4 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe joined [[Scottish Premier League]] club [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]] on loan until the end of the [[2012\u201313 Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C. season|2012\u201313]] season on 25 January 2013.<ref name=\"Inverness CT land Leeds defender Charlie Taylor on loan\">{{Cite news\n| title = Inverness CT land Leeds defender Charlie Taylor on loan\n| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21194175\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 25 January 2013\n| accessdate = 25 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Fleetwood Town (loan)====\n[[File:Charlie Taylor 26-10-2013 1.jpg|thumb|upright|Taylor playing for [[Fleetwood Town F.C.|Fleetwood Town]] in 2013]]\n\nOn 18 October 2013, Taylor joined [[Fleetwood Town F.C.|Fleetwood Town]] on a one-month loan after being signed by manager [[Graham Alexander]].<ref name=\"Taylor strengthens defence\">{{Cite web\n| title = Taylor strengthens defence\n| url = http://www.fleetwoodtownfc.com/news/article/taylor-strengthens-defence-1115634.aspx\n| publisher = Fleetwood Town F.C.\n| date = 18 October 2013\n| accessdate = 18 October 2013}}</ref> Taylor made his debut for Fleetwood Town on the same day, playing in a 2\u20130 defeat against [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]].<ref name=\"Southend 2 Fleetwood 0\">{{Cite news\n| title = Southend 2 Fleetwood 0\n| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24486575\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 18 October 2013\n| accessdate = 18 October 2013}}</ref> After impressing in his first month at the club, on 6 November, Taylor's loan was extended until January 2014.<ref name=\"Leeds United's Charlie Taylor extends Fleetwood Town loan deal\">{{Cite news\n| title = Leeds United's Charlie Taylor extends Fleetwood Town loan deal\n| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24837110\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 6 November 2013\n| accessdate = 6 November 2013}}</ref> After extending Taylor's loan, manager Graham Alexander announced his delight in being able to keep Taylor,<ref name=\"Grezza delighted to keep Charlie at Town\">{{Cite news\n| title = Grezza delighted to keep Charlie at Town\n| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/sport/fleetwood-town/grezza-delighted-to-keep-charlie-at-town-1-6221945\n|newspaper=Blackpool Gazette\n| date = 7 November 2013\n| accessdate = 7 November 2013}}</ref> with Taylor earning rave reviews for his performances.<ref name=\"Young Charlie's been the talk of the Town\">{{cite news\n| title = Young Charlie's been the talk of the Town\n| url = http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/latest-whites-news/leeds-united-young-charlie-s-been-the-talk-of-the-town-1-6221728\n|newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |location=Leeds\n| date = 7 November 2013\n| accessdate = 7 November 2013}}</ref> On 17 December, his loan was extended to the end of the season.<ref name=\"Taylor extends Fleetwood stay\">{{Cite news\n| title = Taylor extends Fleetwood stay\n| url = http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11065/9078006/taylor-extends-fleetwood-stay\n| publisher = Sky Sports\n| date = 17 December 2013\n| accessdate = 17 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nTaylor's form helped Fleetwood Town qualify for the play-off's with a fourth-placed finish in League Two. Fleetwood Town semi-final opponents were Taylor's old club [[York City F.C.|York City]], with Taylor revealing in an interview on 10 May that he wanted to prove people wrong at his former club.<ref name=\"Taylor ready to face hometown club\">{{Cite web\n| title = Taylor ready to face hometown club\n| url = http://www.fleetwoodtownfc.com/news/article/taylor-ready-to-face-hometown-club-1543713.aspx\n| publisher = Fleetwood Town F.C.\n| date = 10 May 2014\n| accessdate = 10 May 2014}}</ref> On 13 May, it was reported that Taylor had impressed new Leeds United owner [[Massimo Cellino]] who was looking at offering Taylor an extended three-year contract, with Taylor's current contract due to expire.<ref name=\"Leeds United: Charlie Taylor set to land new contract\">{{cite news\n| title = Leeds United: Charlie Taylor set to land new contract\n| url = http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/latest-whites-news/leeds-united-charlie-taylor-set-to-land-new-contract-1-6614671\n|newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |location=Leeds\n| date = 13 May 2014\n| accessdate = 13 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter helping guide Fleetwood Town to the League Two play-off's final against [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]], on 20 May Taylor signed a three-year contract extension at his parent club Leeds United. The deal would keep Taylor at the club until 2017.<ref name=\"CHARLIE SIGNS UP\">{{Cite web\n| title = CHARLIE SIGNS UP\n| url = http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/16rgx4lk8mo781m082hn7gx1l6/title/charlie-signs-up\n| publisher = Leeds United F.C.\n| date = 20 May 2014\n| accessdate = 20 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 May, Taylor started the League Two play-off final against Burton Albion. Fleetwood gained promotion with a 1\u20130 victory after a goal from Taylor's teammate [[Antoni Sarcevic]].<ref>{{Cite news\n| title = Burton 0 \u2013 Fleetwood 1 : League 2 Playoff Final\n| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27465323\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 26 May 2014\n| accessdate = 26 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Leeds return===\n====2014\u201315 season====\nOn 1 August, Taylor was assigned the number 21 shirt for the 2014\u201315 season.<ref name=\"SQUAD NUMBERS RELEASED\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/1wncxa2kw0zr11fmlyjr0m3t53/title/squad-numbers-released|title=Squad Numbers Released|publisher=Leeds United F.C.|date=1 August 2014 |accessdate=1 August 2014}}</ref> Taylor made his first start for Leeds since returning from loan on 12 August 2014, starting the League Cup match against [[Accrington Stanley F.C.|Accrington Stanley]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Leeds V Accrington|url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/17zjc7q85j4pm1c43n56bi1r92/title/accrington-live!|publisher=Leeds United F.C.|accessdate=12 August 2014|date=12 August 2014}}</ref> Taylor replaced [[Stephen Warnock]] in Leeds' 1\u20130 victory against [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] on 30 August.<ref>{{cite web |title=Leeds Vs Bolton Wanderers|date=30 August 2014|accessdate=30 August 2014|url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/3fqrhs11d9xa18kq62h7zlkrz/title/bolton-live!|publisher=Leeds United F.C.}}</ref>\n\nAfter the then captain Stephen Warnock suffered an injury in a league match against [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] on 30 December 2014, Taylor came back into the starting lineup on 4 January 2015 in Leeds' [[FA Cup]] 1\u20130 defeat against [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/329650/report|title=Sunderland 1 Leeds 0| date=4 January 2015|accessdate=4 January 2015|publisher=Sky Sports}}</ref> The form of Taylor coming into the team saw regular left back Warnock sold to Derby.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/latest-whites-news/leeds-united-defender-cooper-looks-set-to-be-whites-new-captain-1-7053911|title=Leeds United: Defender Cooper looks set to be Whites' new captain| date=15 January 2015|accessdate=15 January 2015|newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |location=Leeds}}</ref>\n\nAfter impressing at left back, Taylor was played as a left winger for Leeds under Coach [[Neil Redfearn]] as part of a new 4\u20132\u20133\u20131 formation, with [[Gaetano Berardi]] filling in the left back slot. Taylor scored his first goal for Leeds in a 4\u20133 loss against [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Dave Edwards headed home a late winner as Wolves beat Leeds|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32111079 |date=6 April 2015 |accessdate=6 April 2015 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April, after rumoured Premier League interest in Taylor and teammates [[Lewis Cook (footballer, born 1997)|Lewis Cook]], [[Alex Mowatt]] and [[Sam Byram]], head coach [[Neil Redfearn]] challenged Leeds United's owners to keep a hold of their home grown talents.<ref>{{cite news |title=Keep young stars, Redfearn challenges Leeds |url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/latest-whites-news/leeds-united-keep-young-stars-redfearn-challenges-leeds-1-7202015 |date=9 April 2015 |accessdate=9 April 2015 |newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |location=Leeds |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150415180425/http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/latest-whites-news/leeds-united-keep-young-stars-redfearn-challenges-leeds-1-7202015 |archive-date=15 April 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nTaylor scored his second goal for the club on 25 April in a 2\u20131 win against Yorkshire rivals [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Sheffield Wednesday 1\u20132 Leeds United|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32362055 |date=25 April 2015 |accessdate=26 April 2015 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 2 May 2015, Taylor was also nominated for Young Player of the Year Award, but missed out to Lewis Cook.<ref>{{cite web |title= Mowatt Scoops Awards Night Double |date=2 May 2015|url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/slzwndu1a9wb1kdweft4sskxz/title/mowatt-scoops-awards-night-double|publisher=Leeds United F.C.}}</ref>\n\n====2015\u201316 season====\n[[File:Charlie Taylor 1993.jpg|thumb|upright|Taylor celebrating a goal for [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] in 2015]]\n\nOn 19 September 2015, Taylor scored the winner for Leeds against [[Milton Keynes Dons F.C.|Milton Keynes Dons]] in a 2\u20131 victory, with an impressive solo goal running from his own half before scoring a left footed shot.<ref>{{cite news|title= MK Dons 1\u20132 Leeds: Chris Wood and Charlie Taylor goals enough for victory|date=19 September 2015|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/mk-dons-vs-leeds/339622|publisher=Sky Sports}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 April, Taylor was nominated for the Leeds United player of the year award, alongside [[Mirco Antenucci]], [[Liam Bridcutt]], [[Gaetano Berardi]] and [[Lewis Cook (footballer, born 1997)|Lewis Cook]].<ref>{{cite web | title= Player of the Year: Top 5 Vote!| url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/168ovfdrck3da1m2zselrih16n/title/player-of-the-year-top-5-vote! |publisher= Leeds United F.C. | date= 19 April 2016 | accessdate= 19 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 April 2016, at the club's annual Player of the Year Awards, Taylor was named The Fans Player of the Year for the 2015\u201316 season. On the same day Taylor also won the ''[[Yorkshire Evening Post]]''{{'}}s Player of the Year Award.<ref name=POTY>{{cite web |title=Taylor crowned Player of the Year |url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/41r05ixj1r961pyc64yxluocb/title/taylor-crowned-player-of-the-year |publisher=Leeds United F.C. |date=30 April 2016 |accessdate=2 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter being linked with several [[Premier League]] clubs including [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] and [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]], on 15 June 2016, Leeds owner [[Massimo Cellino]] revealed he had approached Taylor's agent about extending Taylors contract, however he said upon a possible contract extension ''Charlie is going to be a problem, I think his agent is the same as [[Sam Byram]]. Taylor doesn't return the call''.<ref>{{cite news | title= Leeds confident of securing Bournemouth target Lewis Cook on fresh terms&nbsp;... but fear Charlie Taylor will not sign a new deal| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-3643473/Leeds-confident-securing-Bournemouth-target-Lewis-Cook-fresh-terms-fear-Charlie-Taylor-not-sign-new-deal.html |newspaper= Daily Mail |location=London | date= 15 June 2016 | accessdate= 15 June 2016}}{{Unreliable source?|date=October 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2016\u201317 season====\nOn 2 August 2016, with speculation still linking Taylor with a move to the Premier League, Leeds announced they had rejected a transfer request from Taylor to leave the club, with the club advising that chairman [[Massimo Cellino]] had said Taylor would not be sold.<ref>{{cite web | title= Club Statement: Charlie Taylor| url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/2nuz0hb14ylq1cb1bw1p0162c |publisher= Leeds United F.C. | date= 2 August 2016 | accessdate= 2 August 2016}}</ref> On 22 August, after Leeds's 2\u20130 victory against [[Sheffield Wednesday]] Taylor proclaimed ''I am contracted until the end of this season, so if they (Leeds) do not want to sell me, then I am under contract. It is up to them and their decision and if they keep me, then I will be until then.''<ref>{{cite news | title= Leeds United: Charlie Taylor keen for future to be resolved as Premier League trio eye classy defender| url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-charlie-taylor-keen-for-future-to-be-resolved-as-premier-league-trio-eye-classy-defender-1-8081598 |newspaper= Yorkshire Evening Post |location=Leeds | date= 22 August 2016 | accessdate= 22 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nTaylor stayed at the club, and despite speculation on his long term future at the club, Taylor was an impressive performer as his performances at Left-back helped Leeds reach 5th place and a playoff position at Christmas 2016.<ref>{{cite news | title= Leeds starlet Charlie Taylor could be the next academy product to follow Sam Byram out of Elland Road| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-4060036/Leeds-starlet-Charlie-Taylor-academy-product-leave-Elland-Road.html |newspaper= Daily Mail |location=London | date= 22 December 2016 | accessdate= 23 December 2016}}{{Unreliable source?|date=October 2017}}</ref> On 29 December 2016, Taylor missed his first Leeds match after 52 consecutive starts, in the match against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in a 1\u20131 draw after picking up an achilles injury against [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] in the previous match.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/match-reports/aston-villa-1-leeds-united-12383620|title=Aston Villa 1 Leeds 1 |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=29 December 2016|accessdate=29 December 2016}}</ref> The injury would keep Taylor out for several months, also added to the form of Left-back [[Gaetano Berardi]], Taylor was unable to reclaim his place in the team.\n\nIn the final match of the season with Leeds missing out on the play-offs bar an almost impossible mathematical goal difference swing, it was revealed by Head coach [[Garry Monk]] that Taylor had refused to play for Leeds in the final match. As a result of the refusal, Taylor was fined two weeks wages by the club with Monk proclaiming \"I'm hugely disappointed with Charlie. I think he's been terribly advised all season.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39844095|title=Charlie Taylor: Leeds boss Garry Monk unhappy after defender misses Wigan game|publisher=BBC Sport|date=8 May 2017|accessdate=8 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 May 2017, it was announced that Taylor had been offered a 2-year contract with the club in line with EFL regulations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/21895/2017-18-retained-list|title=2017/18 Retained List|publisher=Leeds United F.C. |date=17 May 2017|accessdate=17 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Burnley===\nOn 6 July 2017, Taylor signed a four-year contract with Premier League club [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]]. Since Taylor was under 24, Burnley owed Leeds United compensation, which was due to be set at a [[Tribunals in the United Kingdom|tribunal]].<ref>{{cite web|date=6 July 2017|accessdate=6 July 2017|url=https://www.burnleyfootballclub.com/news/2017/july/taylor-raring-to-go-following-turf-move/|publisher=Burnley F.C.|title=Taylor Raring To Go Following Turf Move}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=6 July 2017|accessdate=6 July 2017|url=https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/22023/club-statement-charlie-taylor|publisher=Leeds United F.C.|title=Club Statement: Charlie Taylor}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/charlie-taylor-completes-his-move-from-leeds-united-to-burnley-1-8634575 |title=Charlie Taylor completes his move from Leeds United to Burnley |newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |location=Leeds |date=6 July 2017|accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref> On 25 July 2017, it was reported by the ''Yorkshire Evening Post'' that the clubs had agreed on a compensation of between \u00a36&nbsp;million and \u00a37&nbsp;million to be paid by Burnley to Leeds United for the player, avoiding the need for a tribunal decision.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-whites-agree-fee-with-burnley-over-taylor-move-1-8668936|title=Leeds United: Whites agree fee with Burnley over Taylor move|newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |location=Leeds |accessdate=15 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nIn October 2011, Taylor made his debut for the England under-19 team, playing in two of the three matches in the Limoges Tournament to help England earn a win in the overall tournament.<ref name=\"LUFC Leeds youngster helps England win tournament\"/> His debut came as a substitute against [[Portugal national under-19 football team|Portugal]], before starting against [[Ukraine national under-19 football team|Ukraine]].<ref name=\"LUFC Leeds youngster helps England win tournament\"/>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|match played 7 March 2020}}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|+ Appearances and goals b