h-century American scientists]]\n[[Category:Mathematicians from Maryland]]\n", "name_user": "Corker1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBanneker's almanacs:revise reference", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benjamin_Banneker"}
{"title_page": "No Me Queda M\u00e1s", "text_new": "{{short description|1994 single by Selena}}\n{{featured article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = No Me Queda M\u00e1s\n| cover      = Nomequedamas.jpg\n| alt        = A woman sits on a fallen tree next to a lake, with the subject and its surroundings framed in a pink and blue hue background and titled with the singer's name and song.\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Selena]]\n| album      = [[Amor Prohibido]]\n| released   = October 1994\n| format     = {{flatlist|\n*[[Compact disc single|CD single]]\n*[[12\" single]]\n*[[cassette single|cassette]]\n}}\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Mariachi]]\n*[[bolero]]\n*[[ranchera]]\n*[[soft rock]]\n}}\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=16}} <small>(original version)</small><br /> {{Duration|m=3|s=49}} <small>(re-release version)</small>\n| label      = [[EMI Latin]]\n| writer     = [[Ricky Vela]]\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n*[[A.B. Quintanilla]]\n*[[Bebu Silvetti]]\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Bidi Bidi Bom Bom]]\n| prev_year  = 1994\n| next_title = [[Fotos y Recuerdos]]\n| next_year  = 1995\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|FCi-Xp2TVoQ|\"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\"}}}}\n{{External music video|type= single|header=Audio|1={{youtube|rl1tecAQZ3I|\"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''No Me Queda M\u00e1s'''\" (\"There's Nothing Left for Me\") is a song by American singer [[Selena]] on her fourth studio album, ''[[Amor Prohibido]]''. It was released as the third [[single (music)|single]] from the album in October 1994 by [[EMI Latin]]. \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" was written by [[Ricky Vela]], and production was handled by Selena's brother [[A.B. Quintanilla]]. A [[tempo|downtempo]] [[mariachi]] and [[pop ballad]], \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" portrays the [[ranchera]] storyline of a woman in agony after the end of a relationship. Its lyrics express an [[unrequited love]], the singer wishing the best for her former lover and his new partner.\n\nPraised by [[music journalism|music critics]] for its emotive nature, \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" was one of the most successful singles of Selena's career. It topped the United States [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] [[Hot Latin Songs]] chart for seven non-consecutive weeks, her third successive number-one song. It was Selena's first number-one track on the US [[Regional Mexican Airplay]] chart, and became [[Billboard Top Latin Songs Year-End Chart|the most successful US Latin single of 1995]]. It has been ranked the ninth-best [[Tejano music|Tejano]] recording by ''Billboard'' magazine and the eleventh-best Hot Latin Songs chart single in 2011.\n\nThe [[music video]] for \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" was shot in [[San Antonio]]'s [[Amtrak]] station. It received the Music Video of the Year award at the [[Billboard Latin Music Awards|''Billboard'' Latin Music Awards]], and the recording received two [[Broadcast Music, Inc.|Broadcast Music]] honors including Song of the Year. Many musicians have since recorded [[cover version]]s, including Mexican singer [[Pepe Aguilar]], American salsa singer [[Tito Nieves]], and Mexican pop group Palomo. The Palomo version peaked at number six on the Regional Mexican Airplay chart, while Nieves' version reached number seven on the US [[Tropical Songs]] chart.\n\n==Inspiration, writing and production==\nIn 1985, [[Ricky Vela]] joined [[Selena y Los Dinos]] as their [[keyboardist]].{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=62}} Although Vela was attracted to the group's drummer, [[Suzette Quintanilla]], he kept his feelings to himself.<ref name=\"hotlatinartists\">{{cite journal|last1=Ramirez|first1=Erika|title=Hot Latin Songs Top Artists|journal=Billboard|date=October 8, 2011|volume=123|issue=35|page=21|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jim-YANOn5AC&pg=RA1-PA20&dq=No+Me+Queda+Mas+Ricky+Vela#v=onepage&q=No%20Me%20Queda%20Mas%20Ricky%20Vela&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref> When he confessed his feelings to Suzette's brother, group manager [[Abraham Quintanilla, III]], he began teasing him about it.<ref name=\"hotlatinartists\"/> After Suzette's September 1993 marriage,{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=111}} Vela wrote \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" and it was given to Selena to record for ''[[Amor Prohibido]]''.<ref name=\"hotlatinartists\"/> Selena's brother [[A.B. Quintanilla]] did not find the song to have any potential; he has said that he later had a change of heart.<ref>{{cite web|title=10 Questions With A.B. Quintanilla|url=http://www.bmi.com/news/entry/10_questions_with_a.b._quintanilla|website=[[Broadcast Music, Inc.]]|accessdate=August 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2002 interview, A.B. said that during a recording session he had asked Selena to record the song for a fifth time. The singer replied, \"What you got there is what you got\" and left to go shopping.<ref name=\"albumnotes\">{{cite AV media notes |title=Amor Prohibido |titlelink=Amor Prohibido|others=[[Selena]] |year=2002|publisher=[[EMI Latin]] |id=724354099403|quote=When we were recording for \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" - I believe she had recorded it in four takes&nbsp;\u2014 and I wanted her to do it again, and she got mad at me. She told me that she wasn't going to sing it again. She said \"I already had it! As a matter of fact, I've had it with you, and this studio, I'm ready to get out of here\" - she kind of threw a fit&nbsp;\u2014 well she kind of didn't throw a fit. We wouldn't want to say a fit, but \"you know I'm gonna go to the mall, and I'm gonna head out so, what you got there is what you got\" - and now looking back at \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\", she really did a beautiful job when recording the track, she had so much passion. The song became a classic. That's what I can remember from one of the beautiful memories I have of the ''Amor Prohibido'' album.}}</ref> He mused, \"Now looking back, she really did a beautiful job when recording the song, she had so much passion. The song became a classic.\"<ref name=\"albumnotes\"/>\n\nAlthough the song was originally intended as a [[mariachi]] track, EMI Latin president [[Jose Behar]] believed that a mariachi recording would not appeal to the [[popular music|popular market]].<ref name=\"hotlatinartists\"/> When the song was set to be released as the third single from the album, the group gave it to Argentine arranger [[Bebu Silvetti]] to rework into a pop-style track,<ref name=\"hotlatinartists\"/> and Behar asked Silvetti to \"sweeten\" the song to boost its airplay and chart performance.<ref name=\"mixed\">{{cite journal|title=The Chart Toppers|journal=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=8 January 2000|volume=112|issue=2|pages=116|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kw0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA107&dq=Pepe+Aguilar+no+me+queda+mas#v=onepage&q=Pepe%20Aguilar%20no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref> The result enhanced Selena's pop-radio success and was included in late 1994 reissues of ''Amor Prohibido'', subsequently replacing the original album version.<ref name=\"mixed\"/> Behar said in a [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] interview that the song was \"internalized\" without affecting the originality of its recording.<ref name=\"mixed\"/>\n\n==Music, theme and lyrics==\n{{Listen|filename=No Me Queda Mas.ogg|title=\"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" (1994)|description=20-second sample of \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\", where the singer finds \"the strength to walk away\", and is believed by Ramiro Burr to showcase the singer's ability to \"fully conveyed the pain of love and the tone of redemption\".{{sfn|Burr|1999|p=189}}|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n\"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" is a [[tempo|downtempo]] [[mariachi]] and [[pop ballad]], incorporating [[ranchera]] and [[flamenco music|flamenco]] influences into its sound.{{sfn|Perone|2012|p=84}}{{sfn|Rodriguez|2008|p=126}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Young|first=Bob|title=Music Star crossed Selena's dream of mainstream acceptance is alive and well|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/bostonherald/access/14021238.html?dids=14021238:14021238&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Mar+27%2C+1997&author=BOB+YOUNG&pub=Boston+Herald&desc=Music+Star+crossed+Selena's+dream+of+mainstream+acceptance+is+alive+and+well&pqatl=google|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=[[Boston Globe]]|date=27 March 1997|url-access=subscription }}</ref> Musicologists [[Ilan Stavans]] and [[Harold Augenbraum]] called the song a [[bolero]]-mariachi mix.{{sfn|Stavans|Augenbraum|2005|p=91}} This was echoed by the ''[[Lexington Herald-Leader]]'', which noted its bolero influences.<ref>{{cite news|title=Selena's Last Performance On New DVD|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LH&s_site=kentucky&p_multi=LH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0FD565B89474BC1E&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=[[Lexington Herald-Leader]]|date=31 August 2003|url-access=subscription }}</ref> ''[[Texas Monthly]]'' editor Joe Nick Patoski wrote that Vela \"riffed off romantic boleros\" and the song \"showcase[d] Selena's [[vocal range]] and control\".{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=125}} \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" has a \"traditional [mariachi] [[trumpet]] duet harmony\",{{sfn|Perone|2012|p=84}} using [[violin]]s and [[guitar]]s.{{sfn|Rodriguez|2008|p=126}} The original version mainly used acoustic strummed guitars and a [[Synthesizer|synthesized]] [[string (music)|string]] track; while the single remix, featured on later reissues of ''Amor Prohibido'', replaced this with [[soft rock]] instrumentation featuring a [[drum kit]], [[bass guitar]] and multitracked acoustic and electric guitars combined with a lush live orchestral string arrangement.<ref name=\"newsday\">{{cite news|last=Schone|first=Mark|title=A Postmortem Star In death, Selena is a crossover success|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/newsday/access/20467875.html?dids=20467875:20467875&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Apr+20%2C+1995&author=By+Mark+Schone.+Mark+Schone+is+a+free-lance+writer.&pub=Newsday+(Combined+editions)&desc=A+Postmortem+Star+In+death%2C+Selena+is+a+crossover+success&pqatl=google|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=[[Newsday]]|date=20 April 1995|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nThe song employs the traditional ranchera storyline, with the female singer agonizing over the end of a relationship.{{sfn|Perone|2012|p=84}}{{sfn|Rodriguez|2008|p=126}} Its lyrics explore unrequited love; when the singer's lover leaves her for another woman, she nevertheless wishes them \"nothing but happiness.\"{{sfn|Rodriguez|2008|p=126}}{{sfn|Blumenthal|1997|p=150}} According to author Lori Beth Rodriguez, Selena sings the song \"in a low, sober voice\", and critic [[Howard Blumenthal]] adds that she does so in a \"desperate\" and \"sentimental\" way.{{sfn|Rodriguez|2008|p=126}}{{sfn|Blumenthal|1997|p=150}} Ramiro Burr of the ''[[San Antonio Express-News]]'' called her [[overdubbing|overdubbed]] vocals \"powerful\" and \"emotive\";<ref>{{cite news|last=Burr|first=Ramiro|title=Selena: \u00a1Vive!, Celebrates A Musical Legacy|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SAEC&p_theme=saec&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=1125AE5A35E3C2D8&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=San Antonio Express-News|date=14 April 2005|url-access=subscription }}</ref> other critics have described \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" as \"torchy\",{{sfn|Hoffman|2005}} \"mournful\",<ref>{{cite news|last=Tarradell|first=Mario|title=Selena clip named top video Early Tejano Music Awards hint at those to be named|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DM&p_theme=dm&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0ED3D5A3735CD356&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|date=11 February 1995|url-access=subscription }}</ref> \"piercing\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Tarradell|first=Mario|title=A Decade of Selena: 10 albums showcase the music behind the legend|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DM&p_theme=dm&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0ED82219958E6E11&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|date=30 March 2000|url-access=subscription }}</ref> and \"heartbreaking\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Tarradell|first=Mario|title=Dreaming of Selena A new album celebrates what she was but only hints at what she could have become|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DM&p_theme=dm&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0ED3D5DDAA01CD52&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=The Dallas Morning News|date=16 July 1995|url-access=subscription }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Burr|first=Ramiro|title=Selena Library|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SAEC&p_theme=saec&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=1093099BEF1FAEC2&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=[[San Antonio Express-News]]|date=31 March 2005|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception and impact==\n\"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" was well-received, reviewers describing it as \"evocative\",<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cobo|first1=Leila|title=Reviews & Previews|journal=Billboard|date=April 14, 2001|volume=113|issue=15|page=30|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=whMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA30&dq=Selena+no+me+queda+mas#v=onepage&q=Selena%20no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref> \"romantic\",{{sfn|Paredez|2009|p=203}} and \"bittersweet\";<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Verna|first1=Paul|title=Album Reviews|journal=Billboard|date=April 2, 1994|volume=106|issue=14|page=52|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OQgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA52&dq=Selena+no+me+queda+mas#v=onepage&q=Selena%20no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref> A.B.'s use of \"[[world music|world-music]] flourishes\" on the song was noted approvingly by Michael Clark.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Clark|first1=Michael D.|title=Ten years after her murder, Selena lives on|url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/entertainment/music/article/Ten-years-after-her-murder-Selena-lives-on-1670323.php|accessdate=14 April 2016|work=San Antonio Express News|date=March 25, 2005}}</ref> Writing in ''[[The Billboard Guide to Tejano and Regional Mexican Music]]'', Ramiro Burr felt that the lyrics, about \"finding the strength to walk away\", evoked \"the pain of love and the tone of redemption\".{{sfn|Burr|1999|p=189}} The song became an \"instant classic\", according to Roger Burns, writing in ''Icons of Latino America''.{{sfn|Burns|2008|p=465}} Other reviewers agreed that it was one of the most successful singles from ''Amor Prohibido'',{{sfn|Stavans|Augenbraum|2005|p=91}}{{sfn|Velasquez|2010}}<ref name=\"Onet.pl\">{{cite news|title=16. rocznica \u015bmierci Seleny |url=http://muzyka.onet.pl/10172,2261481,newsy.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320023923/http://muzyka.onet.pl/10172,2261481,newsy.html |archivedate=March 20, 2012 |newspaper=[[Onet.pl]] |date=31 March 2011 |accessdate=14 April 2011 |language=Polish |url-status=dead }}</ref> with Lisa Leal of [[KVTV]] commenting that the song is a Spanish-language counterpart of [[the Beatles]]' 1965 single \"[[Yesterday (Beatles song)|Yesterday]]\" in fan popularity.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Leal|first1=Lisa|title=Fans pay tribute to fallen Tejano Star Selena|url=http://www.kztv10.com/story/28677490/fans-pay-tribute-to-fallen-tejano-star-selena|website=[[KVTV|KVTV.com]]|accessdate=19 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180404175954/http://www.kztv10.com/story/28677490/fans-pay-tribute-to-fallen-tejano-star-selena|archive-date=April 4, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe track received several awards and accolades. It was the Song of the Year at the 1995 [[Broadcast Music, Inc.|Broadcast Music Awards]],<ref name=\"Songoftheyear\">{{cite journal|year=1997 |title=''Billboard'' Latin Awards |journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |volume= |issue= |pages=138 |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AQoEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA85&dq=Kat+DeLuna+No+Me+Queda+Mas#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=14 April 2011 }}</ref> and Vela received the Songwriter of the Year award in 1996.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Burr|first1=Ramiro|title=Pete Astudillo Leads BMI Latin Music Awards|journal=Billboard|date=May 18, 1996|volume=108|issue=20|pages=4, 68|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uA0EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=RA1-PA68&vq=no%20me%20queda%20mas&dq=bmi%20latin%20awards%201996%20intitle%3Abillboard&pg=RA1-PA68#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=8 July 2016}}</ref> Its video was honored as the Music Video of the Year at the 1995 [[Billboard Latin Music Awards|''Billboard'' Latin Music Awards]].<ref name=\"latinmusicawards\">{{cite news|title=''Billboard'', Univision present awards|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=ST&s_site=dfw&p_multi=ST&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAF9009A9E2EBDA&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]|date=9 June 1995|url-access=subscription }}</ref><ref name=\"musicvideo\">{{cite journal |author= |year=1995 |title=And The Latin Music Awards Goes To&nbsp;. |journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |volume=107 |issue=23 |pages=112 |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |doi= |pmid= |pmc= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0QsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA54&dq=no+me+queda+mas#v=onepage&q=no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false |accessdate=14 April 2011 }}</ref> \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" was ranked as the ninth-best Tejano song of all time on Ramiro Burr's top-ten list.{{sfn|Burr|1999|p=229}} It has appeared on several critics' \"best Selena songs\" lists, including [[BuzzFeed]] (at number one),<ref name=brain>{{cite web|last1=Galindo|first1=Brain|title=Ranking The 15 Greatest Selena Songs Ever|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/briangalindo/ranking-the-15-greatest-selena-songs-ever#13h00pr|website=[[BuzzFeed]]|publisher=BuzzFeed Inc|accessdate=October 1, 2014}}</ref> ''Latino Post'' (number four),<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sim\u00f3n|first1=Yara|title=Selena Day 2014: Countdown of Selena's Top 5 Songs|url=http://www.latinopost.com/articles/5586/20140415/selena-day-2014-countdown-of-selenas-top-5-songs.htm|website=Latino Post|accessdate=August 20, 2015}}</ref> and ''[[Latina (magazine)|Latina]]'' (number five).<ref name=latina>{{cite web|last1=Rodriguez|first1=Priscillia|title=Remembering Selena: Her Top Ten Songs|url=http://www.latina.com/music/selena-quintanilla-hit-songs-videos#5|website=Latina|publisher=Lauren Michaels|accessdate=October 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n''Billboard'' announced that a new airplay-measuring system for its music charts would be based on [[Nielsen rating]]s beginning on November 12, 1994.<ref name=newsystem>{{cite journal|last1=Lannert|first1=John|title=Hot Latin Songs > November 4, 1994|journal=Billboard|date=November 4, 1994|volume=106|issue=45|page=46|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YwgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA46&dq=Selena#v=onepage&q=Selena&f=false|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref> \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" entered the US [[Hot Latin Songs]] chart at number 40 on that date, and Selena's \"[[Bidi Bidi Bom Bom]]\" remained at number one.<ref name=newsystem/> On November 19, the song rose to number ten on that chart and subsequently debuted on the US [[Regional Mexican Airplay]] chart at number seven.<ref name=\"nov19\">{{cite journal|title=Hot Latin Songs > November 19, 1994|journal=Billboard|date=November 19, 1994|volume=106|issue=46|page=50|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZggEAAAAMBAJ&dq=billboard&q=no+me+queda+mas#v=snippet&q=no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016|author1=Nielsen Business Media|first1=Inc}}</ref> The following week, it climbed to the fifth and fourth positions on the Hot Latin Songs and Regional Mexican Airplay charts, respectively.<ref name=\"nov26\">{{cite journal|last1=Lannert|first1=John|title=Latin Notas|journal=Billboard|date=November 26, 1994|volume=106|issue=48|page=62|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aggEAAAAMBAJ&dq=billboard&q=no+me+queda+mas#v=snippet&q=no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref> ''Billboard'' contributor John Lannert, noting that three different songs had topped the Hot Latin Songs chart since the inception of the Nielsen-rating system, predicted that [[Luis Miguel]]'s number one single \"La Media Vuelta\" could be unseated by \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\".<ref name=\"nov26\"/> The following week, \"La Media Vuelta\" remained atop the chart and \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" rose to number two.<ref name=\"dec3\">{{cite journal|title=Hot Latin Songs > December 3, 1994|journal=Billboard|date=December 3, 1994|volume=106|issue=49|page=38|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZwgEAAAAMBAJ&dq=billboard&q=no+me+queda+mas#v=snippet&q=no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref> \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" topped the Regional Mexican Airplay chart for three consecutive weeks beginning on December 3, Selena's first number one on that chart.<ref name=\"dec3\"/><ref name=\"dec24\">{{cite journal|title=Regional Mexican Airplay > December 24, 1994|journal=Billboard|date=December 24, 1994|volume=106|issue=52|page=57|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZAgEAAAAMBAJ&dq=billboard&q=no+me+queda+mas#v=snippet&q=no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016|author1=Nielsen Business Media|first1=Inc}}</ref> The song peaked at number one on the Hot Latin Songs chart on December 17, her third consecutive number one.<ref name=\"dec17\">{{cite journal|title=Hot Latin Songs > December 17, 1994|journal=Billboard|date=December 17, 1994|volume=106|issue=50|page=25|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/90s/1994/BB-1994-12-17.pdf|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref> It debuted at number 13 on the US [[Latin Pop Songs]] chart on January 7, 1995, remaining atop the Hot Latin Songs chart.<ref name=\"jan7\">{{cite journal|title=Hot Latin Songs > January 7, 1995|journal=Billboard|date=January 7, 1995|volume=107|issue=1|page=29|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ugsEAAAAMBAJ&dq=billboard&q=no+me+queda+mas#v=snippet&q=no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016|author1=Nielsen Business Media|first1=Inc}}</ref> The song reclaimed the number-one spot on the Regional Mexican Airplay chart for January 14, unseating [[La Mafia]]'s \"Me Duele Estar Solo\".<ref name=\"jan14\">{{cite journal|title=Hot Latin Songs > January 14, 1995|journal=Billboard|date=January 14, 1995|volume=107|issue=2|page=29|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tQsEAAAAMBAJ&dq=billboard&q=no+me+queda+mas#v=snippet&q=no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016|author1=Nielsen Business Media|first1=Inc}}</ref> La Mafia displaced \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" from the top of the Regional Mexican Airplay and Hot Latin Songs charts on January 21, ending the song's five-week reign on the latter.<ref name=\"jan21\">{{cite journal|last1=Lannert|first1=John|title=Latin Notas|journal=Billboard|date=January 21, 1995|volume=107|issue=3|pages=37, 38|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uAsEAAAAMBAJ&dq=billboard&q=no+me+queda+mas#v=snippet&q=no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"jan21\"/> The following week, \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" regained the top of both charts.<ref name=\"jan28\">{{cite journal|title=Hot Latin Songs > January 28, 1995|journal=Billboard|date=January 28, 1995|volume=107|issue=4|page=39|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sgsEAAAAMBAJ&dq=billboard&q=no+me+queda+mas#v=snippet&q=no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016|author1=Nielsen Business Media|first1=Inc}}</ref> On February 4, it fell to number two on the Regional Mexican Airplay chart and retained the top spot on the Hot Latin Songs chart for its seventh nonconsecutive week.<ref name=\"feb4\">{{cite journal|title=Hot Latin Songs > February 4, 1995|journal=Billboard|date=February 4, 1995|volume=107|issue=5|page=43|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sAsEAAAAMBAJ&dq=billboard&q=no+me+queda+mas#v=snippet&q=no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016|author1=Nielsen Business Media|first1=Inc}}</ref> It was displaced from the top of the Hot Latin Songs chart on February 11 by [[Grupo Bronco]]'s \"Que No Me Olvide\".<ref name=\"feb11\">{{cite journal|title=Hot Latin Songs > February 11, 1995|journal=Billboard|date=February 11, 1995|volume=107|issue=6|page=35|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yAsEAAAAMBAJ&dq=billboard&q=no+me+queda+mas#v=snippet&q=no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016|author1=Nielsen Business Media|first1=Inc}}</ref> It was the most popular song from ''Amor Prohibido'' on Mexican radio.{{sfn|Perone|2012|p=84}}\n\nSelena was [[murder of Selena|shot and killed]] on March 31, 1995 by [[Yolanda Sald\u00edvar]], a friend who was the former manager of the singer's [[Selena Etc.]] boutiques.<ref name=\"Bitch\">{{cite news|title=October 12, 1995, the testimony of Norma Martinez |url=http://www.chron.com/content/chronicle/metropolitan/selena/transcripts/95/10/12/martinez.html |accessdate=September 27, 2015 |work=[[Houston Chronicle]] |date=October 12, 1995 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070715183634/http://www.chron.com/content/chronicle/metropolitan/selena/transcripts/95/10/12/martinez.html |archivedate=July 15, 2007 }}</ref> Four of her singles\u2014\"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\", \"Bidi Bidi Bom Bom\", \"[[Como la Flor]]\" and \"[[Amor Prohibido (song)|Amor Prohibido]]\"\u2014reentered the ''Billboard'' Hot Latin Songs and Regional Mexican Airplay charts on April 15.<ref name=posthumous>{{cite journal|last1=Lannert|first1=John|title=Latin Notas|journal=Billboard|date=15 April 1995|volume=107|issue=15|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7wsEAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=Selena&f=false|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref> \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" placed fifth and eighth on the Hot Latin Songs and Regional Mexican Airplay charts, respectively,<ref name=\"posthumous\"/> and remained in the top ten of the Hot Latin Songs chart for 12 consecutive weeks.<ref name=\"ju1\">{{cite journal|title=Hot Latin Tracks > July 1, 1995|journal=Billboard|date=July 1, 1995|volume=107|issue=26|page=37|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rgsEAAAAMBAJ&dq=billboard&q=no+me+queda+mas#v=snippet&q=no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016|author1=Nielsen Business Media|first1=Inc}}</ref> ''Billboard'' posthumously named Selena the Top Latin Artist of the 1990s in recognition of her fourteen top-ten singles on the Hot Latin Songs chart, including seven number ones.<ref name=\"selena\">{{cite journal| last = Mayfield| first = Geoff| date = December 26, 1999| title = Totally '90s: Diary of a Decade| journal = Billboard| publisher = Nielsen Business Media, Inc.| volume = 111\n| issue = 52| page = YE-16| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=9w0EAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=latin&f=false| accessdate =March 30, 2010}}</ref> \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" was the [[Billboard Top Latin Songs Year-End Chart|most successful US Latin single of 1995]].<ref name=\"billboardmag\">\n{{Cite journal\n| date = November 28, 1998\n| title = Topping The Charts Year By Year\n| journal = Billboard\n| volume = 110\n| issue = 48\n| page = LMQ3\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=MAoEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA38&dq=rudy+la+scala&cd=1#v=onepage&q=rudy%20la%20scala\n| accessdate =March 3, 2010| author1 =\nNielsen Business Media| first1 =\nInc}}</ref><ref name=\"numberonesingles\">{{cite news |title=Remembering Selena's Trailblazing Music |author=Rivas, Jorge |url=http://colorlines.com/archives/2011/03/16th_anniversary_of_selenas_death.html |newspaper=Colorlines |date=March 31, 2011 |accessdate=April 14, 2011}}</ref> It ranked eleventh on ''Billboard''{{'}}s quarter-century celebration of the Hot Latin Songs chart in 2011.<ref name=\"hotlatinartists\"/> ''Billboard'' began monitoring [[music download|digital downloads]] of Latin songs during the week ending January 23, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Latin Digital Songs > January 23, 2010|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2010-01-23/latin-digital-songs|website=Billboard.biz|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=April 14, 2016}}</ref> \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" made its debut at number 23 on the [[Latin Digital Songs]] chart following the twentieth anniversary of Selena's death.<ref>{{cite web|title=Latin Digital Songs > April 18, 2015|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2015-04-18/latin-digital-songs|website=Billboard.biz|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref> On the [[Billboard charts#Latin|Latin Pop Digital Songs]] chart, the song debuted at number 22 and peaked at number nine.<ref>{{cite web|title=Latin Pop Digital > April 11, 2015|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2015-04-11/latin-pop-digital-songs|website=Billboard.biz|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nAn accompanying music video for \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" was filmed in October 1994 at the [[San Antonio]] [[San Antonio station (Texas)|Amtrak station]].<ref name=\"production\">{{cite journal|last1=Bessman|first1=Jim|title=Production Notes|journal=Billboard|date=November 12, 1994|volume=106|issue=46|page=38|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aAgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA38&dq=Selena+No+Me+Queda+Mas#v=onepage&q=Selena%20No%20Me%20Queda%20Mas&f=false|accessdate=25 May 2016}}</ref> Produced by Summit Productions, the video was directed by Sean Roberts.<ref name=\"production\"/> Shooting took four days to complete.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=128}} Jack Morgan was the on-set photographer, and Diego Aguilar produced the video.<ref name=\"production\"/> Selena wore the same dress that she did when she won a [[Grammy Award for Best Mexican/Mexican-American Album|Grammy Award for Best Mexican/American Album]] in [[36th Grammy Awards|1994]].{{sfn|Arrar\u00e1s|1997|p=34}} Veronica Flores, a reporter for the ''San Antonio Express-News'', was asked to make a cameo appearance as a wedding guest.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Flores|first1=Veronica|title=My short, happy friendship with Selena|url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/news/article/My-short-happy-friendship-with-Selena-1646173.php|accessdate=19 April 2016|work=San Antonio Express-News|date=March 25, 2005}}</ref> American model Freddie Martinez portrayed Selena's love interest after auditioning for the role in San Antonio.<ref>{{cite news|title=Selena: Her Voice Will Never Be Silenced|url=http://www.caller.com/entertainment/selena/selena-her-voice-will-never-be-silenced-ep-1039475785.html|accessdate=August 19, 2016|work=[[Corpus Christi Caller-Times]]|date=April 2, 1995}}</ref>\n\nThe video's location was later used for Selena's fashion-show scene in ''[[Selena (film)|Selena]]'' (1997), starring [[Jennifer Lopez]].<ref>{{cite AV media |people=[[Jennifer Lopez]], [[Edward James Olmos]], [[Jon Seda]], [[Jackie Guerra]] |date=March 21, 1997 |title=[[Selena (film)|Selena]] |type=DVD |time=127 minutes |publisher=[[Warner Bros.]] }}</ref> [[Hillary Clinton]] used \"Bidi Bidi Bom Bom\" as part of her [[Hillary Clinton presidential campaign, 2016|2016 presidential campaign]] in San Antonio (which received a mixed response from Hispanics),<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gamboa|first1=Suzanne|title=Hillary Clinton and The 'Abuela' Factor|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/hillary-clinton-abuela-factor-n485226|accessdate=13 April 2016|work=[[NBC News]]|date=December 24, 2015}}</ref> playing the song at the location where Selena recorded the music video for \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Reichard|first1=Raquel|title=Clinton Enters \"Latinos for Hillary\" event in Texas With Selena's 'Bidi Bidi Bom Bom'|url=http://www.latina.com/lifestyle/politics/hillary-clinton-event-selena-bidi-bidi-bom-bom|accessdate=13 April 2016|work=Latina|date=October 16, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426210518/http://www.latina.com/lifestyle/politics/hillary-clinton-event-selena-bidi-bidi-bom-bom|archivedate=April 26, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Univision]] ranked the music video at number four on their top ten favorite music videos of Selena.<ref>{{cite news|title=El Top Ten de los videos de Selena Quintanilla |url=http://www.univision.com/musica/el-top-ten-de-los-videos-de-selena-quintanilla |trans-title=The Top Ten Videos of Selena Quintanilla |accessdate=June 9, 2016 |work=[[Univision]] |date=March 31, 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6i8vEM2Ev?url=http://www.univision.com/musica/el-top-ten-de-los-videos-de-selena-quintanilla |archivedate=June 9, 2016 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn the video, Selena is sitting in a restaurant where a mariachi band is performing. A waiter offers her a glass of water. As the singer enjoys her dinner, the waiter returns with a note saying that her lover (for whom she has been waiting) has left her for another woman. Selena takes a sip of water before she leaves the restaurant, crying.\n\nThe singer is in the dark behind a busy highway, sobbing and peeling petals off a white rose in a game of [[He loves me... he loves me not]] as a [[Montage (filmmaking)|montage]] is playing of images of Selena and her former lover. Selena then sings on a staircase in a white dress, accompanied by an orchestra. She considers crashing her ex-lover's beach wedding, but instead runs away in tears. Selena's ex-lover and his new wife kiss, and a video plays in which he kisses Selena's hands. He then embraces his wife as Selena looks down, sobbing.\n\n==Cover versions==\n{{Multiple image|left|image1=Kat DeLuna 2008-3 cropped.jpg|total_width=300|width1=319|height1=560|alt1=Kat DeLuna dancing onstage in a short, black dress|image2=Pepe Aguilar cropped.jpg|width2=250|height2=323|alt2=Pepe Aguilar singing onstage|footer=Dominican singer Kat DeLuna (left) and Mexican singer [[Pepe Aguilar]] have covered \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" in live performances.}}\nAmerican [[salsa music|salsa]] singer [[Tito Nieves]] recorded \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" for his third studio album, ''Un Tipo Comun'' (1996).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Estevez Jr|first1=Jose A.|title=Un Tip Comun > Album Review|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/un-tipo-comun-mw0000645468|website=AllMusic|publisher=Rovi Corporation|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref> The song was commercially more successful than the four singles released from the album, where it peaked at number seven on the US [[Tropical Songs]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=Awards > Un Tipo Comun|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/un-tipo-comun-mw0000645468/awards|website=AllMusic|publisher=Rovi Corporation|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref> That same year, Dominican singer [[Kat DeLuna]] won first place when she sang the song at the New Jersey Hispanic Youth Showcase, a children's singing competition.<ref>{{cite journal|title=I Want To Become A Singer|journal=[[Latina (magazine)|Latina]]|publisher=Latina Publications|date=April 2008|volume=12|issue=4|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sDIrAQAAIAAJ&q=Selena+No+Me+Queda+M%C3%A1s&dq=Selena+No+Me+Queda+M%C3%A1s|accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref> In 1998, [[Los Tres Reyes]] (a mariachi group produced by Abraham Quintanilla, Jr.) recorded a duet version of the song.<ref>{{cite news|last=Burr|first=Ramiro|title=Los Tres Reyes rekindle romantic classics for Mother's Day crowd|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SAEC&p_theme=saec&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAFE83D0869F0D8&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=San Antonio Express-News|date=12 May 1998|url-access=subscription }}</ref> [[Graciela Beltran]] covered the song during a memorial for Selena in [[Houston]] in 2003.<ref>{{cite news|title=The People's Queen' at the fair|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MSSB&p_theme=mssb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=102446A9B35A3CE0&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=[[The Merced Sun-Star]]|date=14 July 2003|url-access=subscription }}</ref> Mexican singer [[Pepe Aguilar]] performed and recorded \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" for a live, televised tribute concert, ''[[Selena \u00a1VIVE!]]'', in April 2005. According to Michael Clark of the ''[[Houston Chronicle]]'', \"[Aguilar's] vocal ... was reminiscent of [[Aaron Neville]]\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Clark|first=Michael|title=Modern, traditional mix in vibrant Selena tribute|url=http://www.chron.com/entertainment/music/article/Modern-traditional-mix-in-vibrant-Selena-tribute-1930189.php|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=[[Houston Chronicle]]|date=8 April 2005}}</ref>\n\nMexican pop group Palomo recorded \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" for their [[live album]], ''En Concierto-En Vivo Desde L.A.'' (2005). The song debuted at number 37 on the Regional Mexican Airplay chart on March 19, 2005,<ref>{{cite journal|title=Regional Mexican Airplay > March 19, 2005|journal=Billboard|date=March 19, 2005|volume=117|issue=12|page=27|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=thQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA27&dq=Palomo+no+me+queda+mas#v=onepage&q=Palomo%20no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016|author1=Nielsen Business Media|first1=Inc}}</ref> and at number 46 on the Hot Latin Songs chart on April 2.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Hot Latin Songs > April 2, 2005|journal=Billboard|date=April 2, 2005|volume=117|issue=14|page=23|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_BMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA23&dq=Palomo+no+me+queda+mas#v=onepage&q=Palomo%20no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016|author1=Nielsen Business Media|first1=Inc}}</ref> It remained on the chart until July 16, peaking at numbers 19 and six on the Hot Latin Songs and Regional Mexican Airplay charts, respectively.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Hot Latin Songs > July 16, 2005|journal=Billboard|date=July 16, 2005|volume=117|issue=29|page=76|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uRQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA76&dq=Palomo+no+me+queda+mas#v=onepage&q=Palomo%20no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016|author1=Nielsen Business Media|first1=Inc}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Chart history > Palomo|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/277178/palomo/chart?f=373|website=Billboard|accessdate=25 June 2016}}</ref> Ricky Vela received a BMI Latin Music Award for the Palomo's cover in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title=BMI Complete List of Winners|url=http://www.bmi.com/press/entry/534979|website=Broadcast Music, Inc.|accessdate=August 25, 2016}}</ref> American singer [[Jos\u00e9 Feliciano]] recorded it for his album, ''Jose Feliciano y Amigos'', in 2006; Ramiro Burr of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' called it a \"bittersweet ranchera\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Burr|first=Ramiro|title=Jose Feliciano teams up with friends on 'Amigos'|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2007-01-17/features/0701160309_1_jose-feliciano-raul-di-blasio-accordion|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=17 January 2007}}</ref> Cuban singer To\u00f1ita recorded the song for her album, ''Desafiando al Destino'', in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title=iTunes > Music > Desafinado al destino|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/desafiando-al-destino/id262298876|work=[[iTunes Store]]|publisher=[[Apple Inc]]|accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref> A year later, American singer Maria Williams recorded an English-language version entitled \"Nothing Left For Me\" for her debut album ''Hybrid''.<ref>{{cite web|title=iTunes > Music > Hybrid|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/hybrid/id295953087|work=iTunes Store|publisher=Apple Inc|accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref> American singer [[David Archuleta]] performed the song as a tribute to Selena at the [[2010 Tejano Music Awards]],<ref>{{Cite episode |title=2010 Tejano Music Awards |episodelink=2010 Tejano Music Awards |series=Tejano Music Awards |serieslink=Tejano Music Awards |network=Telemundo |airdate=July 20, 2010 |language=Spanish}}</ref> and [[Karen Rodriguez]] sang it during the [[American Idol (season 10)|tenth season]] of ''[[American Idol]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cruz Tejada|first=Miguel|title=La dominicana Karen Rodr\u00edguez a un paso de ser  la nueva estrella de American Idol|url=http://elnuevodiario.com.do/app/article.aspx?id=234618|work=El Nuevo Diario|accessdate=21 December 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421114307/http://elnuevodiario.com.do/app/article.aspx?id=234618|archivedate=April 21, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=de Moraes|first=Lisa|title='American Idol' 2011: Top 24 survive the Trail of Tears|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/tvblog/2011/02/american-idol-names-the-top-24.html|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=25 February 2010}}</ref> On May 1, 2015, Jennifer Lopez performed \"[[A Selena Tribute]]\" at the [[2015 Latin Billboard Music Awards]], which included \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Emery|first1=Debby|title=Jennifer Lopez's Touching Tribute to Selena at Billboard Latin Music Awards|url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/entertainment/article/Jennifer-Lopez-s-Touching-Tribute-to-Selena-at-6235210.php|accessdate=20 September 2015|work=San Antonio Express-News|date=May 1, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304052635/http://www.mysanantonio.com/entertainment/article/Jennifer-Lopez-s-Touching-Tribute-to-Selena-at-6235210.php|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Lopez was praised by music critics, who appreciated the singer's Selena-esque costumes.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nessif|first1=Bruna|title=Jennifer Lopez Joins Los Dinos for Beautiful Selena Quintanilla-P\u00e9rez Tribute at 2015 Billboard Latin Music Awards|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/652379/jennifer-lopez-joins-los-dinos-for-beautiful-selena-quintanilla-perez-tribute-at-2015-billboard-latin-music-awards|website=E! News|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=de Valle|first1=Elaine|title=Jennifer Lopez Pays Tribute to Selena at Billboard Latin Music Awards|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/events/latin-awards/6553501/jennifer-lopez-selena-tribute-billboard-latin-music-awards|website=Billboard|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Flashback: Jennifer Lopez Pays Tribute to Slain Singer Selena|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/flashback-jennifer-lopez-pays-tribute-to-slain-singer-selena-20160331|accessdate=14 April 2016|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=March 31, 2016}}</ref> The recording debuted and peaked at number 33 on the Hot Latin Songs chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chart history > Jennifer Lopez|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/304444/jennifer-lopez/chart?f=363|website=Billboard|accessdate=25 June 2016}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Credits and personnel==\nCredits adapted from the [[liner notes]] of ''Amor Prohibido''.<ref name=\"albumnotes\"/>\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n*Selena&nbsp;\u2013 [[Singing|vocals]]\n*Joe Ojeda&nbsp;\u2013 [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]]\n*[[Ricky Vela]]&nbsp;\u2013 writer, [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]]\n*[[Chris P\u00e9rez]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[guitar]]s\n*[[A.B. Quintanilla III]]&nbsp;\u2013 arranger, producer\n*[[Bebu Silvetti]]&nbsp;\u2013 arranger\n*[[Suzette Quintanilla]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[drum kit|drums]]\n{{col-2}}\n*[[Arturo Meza]], Jesse \"O'Jay\" Martinez&nbsp;\u2013 [[percussion]]/[[conga]]s\n*Odalis Smith, Helen Stackhouse, Morgan Taylor&nbsp;\u2013 [[french horn]]\n*Gertrude Myers, Ruth Moore, John Foster, Alice Powell&nbsp;\u2013 [[violin]]\n*Lucy Richardson&nbsp;\u2013 [[cello]]\n*Francisca Malorie, James Watson&nbsp;\u2013 [[flute]]\n*Edward Jackson, Jose Deluna&nbsp;\u2013 [[trumpet]]\n*Freddie Corea, Don Shelton&nbsp;\u2013 [[tambourine]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"|Chart (1994)\n! scope=\"col\"|Peak<br>position\n|-\n!scope=row{{singlechart|Billboardlatinsongs|1|artist=Selena|id={{BillboardID|Selena}}}}\n|-\n!scope=row{{singlechart|Billboardregionalmexican|1|artist=Selena|id={{BillboardID|Selena}}}}\n|-\n!scope=row{{singlechart|Billboardlatinpopsongs|13|artist=Selena|id={{BillboardID|Selena}}}}\n|-\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"|Chart (1995)\n! scope=\"col\"|Position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|US Hot Latin Songs (''Billboard'')<ref>{{cite journal|title=Year-End Charts, ''Billboard''|journal=Billboard|date=28 November 1998|volume=110|issue=48|pages=104|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MAoEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA38|accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|US Regional Mexican Airplay (''Billboard'')<ref name=\"yearend95\">{{cite journal|title=1995 Year In Music|journal=Billboard|date=December 23, 1995|volume=107|issue=51|page=33|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nQ0EAAAAMBAJ|accessdate=May 12, 2015}}</ref>\n|2\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n===All-time charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"|Chart (2018)\n! scope=\"col\"|Position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|US Hot Latin Songs (''Billboard'')<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8475322/the-top-20-latin-songs-of-all-time-billboard-charts|title=The Top 20 Latin Songs of All Time on the Billboard Charts|work=Billboard|last=Bustios|first=Pamela|date=September 15, 2018|accessdate=September 16, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180916032904/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8475322/the-top-20-latin-songs-of-all-time-billboard-charts|archivedate=September 16, 2018}}</ref>\n| 18\n|-\n|}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|title=No Me Queda Mas|artist=Selena|type=single|award=Platinum|number=4|Spanish=yes|certyear=2017}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=yes|noshipments=yes|streaming=true}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia books|Selena|Selena|Amor Prohibido|''Amor Prohibido''}}\n*[[Latin music in the United States]]\n*[[Billboard Top Latin Songs Year-End Chart|''Billboard'' Top Latin Songs Year-End Chart]]\n*[[List of number-one Billboard Hot Latin Tracks of 1994|List of number-one ''Billboard'' Hot Latin Tracks of 1994]]\n*[[List of number-one Billboard Hot Latin Tracks of 1995|List of number-one ''Billboard'' Hot Latin Tracks of 1995]]\n{{clear}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Texas|Music|Latin music|Pop music}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Arrar\u00e1s|first=Mar\u00eda Celeste|authorlink=Mar\u00eda Celeste Arrar\u00e1s|title=Selena's Secret: The Revealing Story Behind Her Tragic Death|year=1997|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=0-684-83193-7|url=https://archive.org/details/selenassecretrev00arra}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Blumenthal|first1=Howard J.|title=The world music CD listener's guide|date=1997|publisher=Billboard Books|location=New York|isbn=0-8230-7663-6|url=https://archive.org/details/worldmusiccdlist00blum}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Burns|first=Roger|title=Icons of Latino America: Latino Contributions to American Culture|year=2008|publisher=Greenwood Press|isbn=0-313-34088-9|volume=2}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Burr|first=Ramiro|title=The Billboard Guide to Tejano and Regional Mexican Music|year=1999|publisher=Billboard books|isbn=0-8230-7691-1|url=https://archive.org/details/billboardguideto00burr}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Hoffman|first=Frank|title=Encyclopedia of Recorded Sound|date=2005|publisher=Routledge|isbn=1-135-94950-6}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Paredez| first =Deborah| title =Selenidad: Selena, Latinos, and the Performance of Memory| year =2009| publisher =[[Duke University Press]]| isbn =0-8223-9089-2}}\n*{{cite book| ref = harv| last = Patoski| first = Joe Nick| title = Selena: Como La Flor| year = 1996| publisher = Little Brown and Company| location = Boston| isbn = 0-316-69378-2| url = https://archive.org/details/selenacomolaflor00pato_0}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Perone|first=James E.|title=The Album: A Guide to Pop Music's Most Provocative, Influential, and Important Creations|date=2012|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=0-313-37907-6}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Rodriguez|first=Lori Beth|title=Mapping Tejana Epistemologies|date=2008|publisher=ProQuest|isbn=0-549-51061-3}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last1=Stavans |first1=Ilan |last2=Augenbraum |first2=Harold |authorlink1=Ilan Stavans|title=Encyclopedia Latina: history, culture, and society in the United States|url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopedialati01stav |url-access=registration |date=2005|publisher=Grolier Academic Reference|isbn=0-7172-5815-7}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Velasquez|first=Jorge|title=Meditaciones para Lograr Su Primer Millon|year=2010|publisher=iUniverse|isbn=1-4502-3731-2}}\n\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{Selena singles}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:No Me Queda Mas}}\n[[Category:1994 singles]]\n[[Category:1994 songs]]\n[[Category:Selena songs]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language songs]]\n[[Category:Ranchera songs]]\n[[Category:Pop ballads]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot Latin Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot Latin Songs number-one singles of the year]]\n[[Category:Billboard Regional Mexican Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Ricky Vela]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by A.B. Quintanilla]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Bebu Silvetti]]\n[[Category:EMI Latin singles]]\n[[Category:Jos\u00e9 Feliciano songs]]\n[[Category:Tito Nieves songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1994 single by Selena}}\n{{featured article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = No Me Queda M\u00e1s\n| cover      = Nomequedamas.jpg\n| alt        = A woman sits on a fallen tree next to a lake, with the subject and its surroundings framed in a pink and blue hue background and titled with the singer's name and song.\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Selena]]\n| album      = [[Amor Prohibido]]\n| released   = October 1994\n| format     = {{flatlist|\n*[[Compact disc single|CD single]]\n*[[12\" single]]\n*[[cassette single|cassette]]\n}}\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Mariachi]]\n*[[bolero]]\n*[[ranchera]]\n*[[soft rock]]\n}}\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=16}} <small>(original version)</small><br /> {{Duration|m=3|s=49}} <small>(re-release version)</small>\n| label      = [[EMI Latin]]\n| writer     = [[Ricky Vela]]\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n*[[A.B. Quintanilla]]\n*[[Bebu Silvetti]]\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Bidi Bidi Bom Bom]]\n| prev_year  = 1994\n| next_title = [[Fotos y Recuerdos]]\n| next_year  = 1995\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|FCi-Xp2TVoQ|\"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\"}}}}\n{{External music video|type= single|header=Audio|1={{youtube|rl1tecAQZ3I|\"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''No Me Queda M\u00e1s'''\" (\"There's Nothing Left for Me\") is a song by American singer [[Selena]] on her fourth studio album, ''[[Amor Prohibido]]''. It was released as the third [[single (music)|single]] from the album in October 1994 by [[EMI Latin]]. \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" was written by [[Ricky Vela]], and production was handled by Selena's brother [[A.B. Quintanilla]]. A [[tempo|downtempo]] [[mariachi]] and [[pop ballad]], \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" portrays the [[ranchera]] storyline of a woman in agony after the end of a relationship. Its lyrics express an [[unrequited love]], the singer wishing the best for her former lover and his new partner.\n\nPraised by [[music journalism|music critics]] for its emotive nature, \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" was one of the most successful singles of Selena's career. It topped the United States [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] [[Hot Latin Songs]] chart for seven non-consecutive weeks, her third successive number-one song. It was Selena's first number-one track on the US [[Regional Mexican Airplay]] chart, and became [[Billboard Top Latin Songs Year-End Chart|the most successful US Latin single of 1995]]. It has been ranked the ninth-best [[Tejano music|Tejano]] recording by ''Billboard'' magazine and the eleventh-best Hot Latin Songs chart single in 2011.\n\nThe [[music video]] for \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" was shot in [[San Antonio]]'s [[Amtrak]] station. It received the Music Video of the Year award at the [[Billboard Latin Music Awards|''Billboard'' Latin Music Awards]], and the recording received two [[Broadcast Music, Inc.|Broadcast Music]] honors including Song of the Year. Many musicians have since recorded [[cover version]]s, including Mexican singer [[Pepe Aguilar]], American salsa singer [[Tito Nieves]], and Mexican pop group Palomo. The Palomo version peaked at number six on the Regional Mexican Airplay chart, while Nieves' version reached number seven on the US [[Tropical Songs]] chart.\n\n==Inspiration, writing and production==\nIn 1985, [[Ricky Vela]] joined [[Selena y Los Dinos]] as their [[keyboardist]].{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=62}} Although Vela was attracted to the group's drummer, [[Suzette Quintanilla]], he kept his feelings to himself.<ref name=\"hotlatinartists\">{{cite journal|last1=Ramirez|first1=Erika|title=Hot Latin Songs Top Artists|journal=Billboard|date=October 8, 2011|volume=123|issue=35|page=21|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jim-YANOn5AC&pg=RA1-PA20&dq=No+Me+Queda+Mas+Ricky+Vela#v=onepage&q=No%20Me%20Queda%20Mas%20Ricky%20Vela&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref> When he confessed his feelings to Suzette's brother, group manager [[Abraham Quintanilla, III]], he began teasing him about it.<ref name=\"hotlatinartists\"/> After Suzette's September 1993 marriage,{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=111}} Vela wrote \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" and it was given to Selena to record for ''[[Amor Prohibido]]''.<ref name=\"hotlatinartists\"/> Selena's brother [[A.B. Quintanilla]] did not find the song to have any potential; he has said that he later had a change of heart.<ref>{{cite web|title=10 Questions With A.B. Quintanilla|url=http://www.bmi.com/news/entry/10_questions_with_a.b._quintanilla|website=[[Broadcast Music, Inc.]]|accessdate=August 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2002 interview, A.B. said that during a recording session he had asked Selena to record the song for a fifth time. The singer replied, \"What you got there is what you got\" and left to go shopping.<ref name=\"albumnotes\">{{cite AV media notes |title=Amor Prohibido |titlelink=Amor Prohibido|others=[[Selena]] |year=2002|publisher=[[EMI Latin]] |id=724354099403|quote=When we were recording for \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" - I believe she had recorded it in four takes&nbsp;\u2014 and I wanted her to do it again, and she got mad at me. She told me that she wasn't going to sing it again. She said \"I already had it! As a matter of fact, I've had it with you, and this studio, I'm ready to get out of here\" - she kind of threw a fit&nbsp;\u2014 well she kind of didn't throw a fit. We wouldn't want to say a fit, but \"you know I'm gonna go to the mall, and I'm gonna head out so, what you got there is what you got\" - and now looking back at \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\", she really did a beautiful job when recording the track, she had so much passion. The song became a classic. That's what I can remember from one of the beautiful memories I have of the ''Amor Prohibido'' album.}}</ref> He mused, \"Now looking back, she really did a beautiful job when recording the song, she had so much passion. The song became a classic.\"<ref name=\"albumnotes\"/>\n\nAlthough the song was originally intended as a [[mariachi]] track, EMI Latin president [[Jose Behar]] believed that a mariachi recording would not appeal to the [[popular music|popular market]].<ref name=\"hotlatinartists\"/> When the song was set to be released as the third single from the album, the group gave it to Argentine arranger [[Bebu Silvetti]] to rework into a pop-style track,<ref name=\"hotlatinartists\"/> and Behar asked Silvetti to \"sweeten\" the song to boost its airplay and chart performance.<ref name=\"mixed\">{{cite journal|title=The Chart Toppers|journal=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=8 January 2000|volume=112|issue=2|pages=116|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kw0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA107&dq=Pepe+Aguilar+no+me+queda+mas#v=onepage&q=Pepe%20Aguilar%20no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref> The result enhanced Selena's pop-radio success and was included in late 1994 reissues of ''Amor Prohibido'', subsequently replacing the original album version.<ref name=\"mixed\"/> Behar said in a [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] interview that the song was \"internalized\" without affecting the originality of its recording.<ref name=\"mixed\"/>\n\n==Music, theme and lyrics==\n{{Listen|filename=No Me Queda Mas.ogg|title=\"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" (1994)|description=20-second sample of \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\", where the singer finds \"the strength to walk away\", and is believed by Ramiro Burr to showcase the singer's ability to \"fully conveyed the pain of love and the tone of redemption\".{{sfn|Burr|1999|p=189}}|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n\"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" is a [[tempo|downtempo]] [[mariachi]] and [[pop ballad]], incorporating [[ranchera]] and [[flamenco music|flamenco]] influences into its sound.{{sfn|Perone|2012|p=84}}{{sfn|Rodriguez|2008|p=126}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Young|first=Bob|title=Music Star crossed Selena's dream of mainstream acceptance is alive and well|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/bostonherald/access/14021238.html?dids=14021238:14021238&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Mar+27%2C+1997&author=BOB+YOUNG&pub=Boston+Herald&desc=Music+Star+crossed+Selena's+dream+of+mainstream+acceptance+is+alive+and+well&pqatl=google|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=[[Boston Globe]]|date=27 March 1997|url-access=subscription }}</ref> Musicologists [[Ilan Stavans]] and [[Harold Augenbraum]] called the song a [[bolero]]-mariachi mix.{{sfn|Stavans|Augenbraum|2005|p=91}} This was echoed by the ''[[Lexington Herald-Leader]]'', which noted its bolero influences.<ref>{{cite news|title=Selena's Last Performance On New DVD|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LH&s_site=kentucky&p_multi=LH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0FD565B89474BC1E&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=[[Lexington Herald-Leader]]|date=31 August 2003|url-access=subscription }}</ref> ''[[Texas Monthly]]'' editor Joe Nick Patoski wrote that Vela \"riffed off romantic boleros\" and the song \"showcase[d] Selena's [[vocal range]] and control\".{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=125}} \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" has a \"traditional [mariachi] [[trumpet]] duet harmony\",{{sfn|Perone|2012|p=84}} using [[violin]]s and [[guitar]]s.{{sfn|Rodriguez|2008|p=126}} The original version mainly used acoustic strummed guitars and a [[Synthesizer|synthesized]] [[string (music)|string]] track; while the single remix, featured on later reissues of ''Amor Prohibido'', replaced this with [[soft rock]] instrumentation featuring a [[drum kit]], [[bass guitar]] and multitracked acoustic and electric guitars combined with a lush live orchestral string arrangement.<ref name=\"newsday\">{{cite news|last=Schone|first=Mark|title=A Postmortem Star In death, Selena is a crossover success|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/newsday/access/20467875.html?dids=20467875:20467875&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Apr+20%2C+1995&author=By+Mark+Schone.+Mark+Schone+is+a+free-lance+writer.&pub=Newsday+(Combined+editions)&desc=A+Postmortem+Star+In+death%2C+Selena+is+a+crossover+success&pqatl=google|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=[[Newsday]]|date=20 April 1995|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nThe song employs the traditional ranchera storyline, with the female singer agonizing over the end of a relationship.{{sfn|Perone|2012|p=84}}{{sfn|Rodriguez|2008|p=126}} Its lyrics explore unrequited love; when the singer's lover leaves her for another woman, she nevertheless wishes them \"nothing but happiness.\"{{sfn|Rodriguez|2008|p=126}}{{sfn|Blumenthal|1997|p=150}} According to author Lori Beth Rodriguez, Selena sings the song \"in a low, sober voice\", and critic [[Howard Blumenthal]] adds that she does so in a \"desperate\" and \"sentimental\" way.{{sfn|Rodriguez|2008|p=126}}{{sfn|Blumenthal|1997|p=150}} Ramiro Burr of the ''[[San Antonio Express-News]]'' called her [[overdubbing|overdubbed]] vocals \"powerful\" and \"emotive\";<ref>{{cite news|last=Burr|first=Ramiro|title=Selena: \u00a1Vive!, Celebrates A Musical Legacy|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SAEC&p_theme=saec&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=1125AE5A35E3C2D8&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=San Antonio Express-News|date=14 April 2005|url-access=subscription }}</ref> other critics have described \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" as \"torchy\",{{sfn|Hoffman|2005}} \"mournful\",<ref>{{cite news|last=Tarradell|first=Mario|title=Selena clip named top video Early Tejano Music Awards hint at those to be named|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DM&p_theme=dm&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0ED3D5A3735CD356&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|date=11 February 1995|url-access=subscription }}</ref> \"piercing\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Tarradell|first=Mario|title=A Decade of Selena: 10 albums showcase the music behind the legend|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DM&p_theme=dm&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0ED82219958E6E11&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|date=30 March 2000|url-access=subscription }}</ref> and \"heartbreaking\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Tarradell|first=Mario|title=Dreaming of Selena A new album celebrates what she was but only hints at what she could have become|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DM&p_theme=dm&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0ED3D5DDAA01CD52&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=The Dallas Morning News|date=16 July 1995|url-access=subscription }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Burr|first=Ramiro|title=Selena Library|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SAEC&p_theme=saec&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=1093099BEF1FAEC2&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=[[San Antonio Express-News]]|date=31 March 2005|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception and impact==\n\"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" was well-received, reviewers describing it as \"evocative\",<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cobo|first1=Leila|title=Reviews & Previews|journal=Billboard|date=April 14, 2001|volume=113|issue=15|page=30|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=whMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA30&dq=Selena+no+me+queda+mas#v=onepage&q=Selena%20no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref> \"romantic\",{{sfn|Paredez|2009|p=203}} and \"bittersweet\";<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Verna|first1=Paul|title=Album Reviews|journal=Billboard|date=April 2, 1994|volume=106|issue=14|page=52|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OQgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA52&dq=Selena+no+me+queda+mas#v=onepage&q=Selena%20no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref> A.B.'s use of \"[[world music|world-music]] flourishes\" on the song was noted approvingly by Michael Clark.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Clark|first1=Michael D.|title=Ten years after her murder, Selena lives on|url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/entertainment/music/article/Ten-years-after-her-murder-Selena-lives-on-1670323.php|accessdate=14 April 2016|work=San Antonio Express News|date=March 25, 2005}}</ref> Writing in ''[[The Billboard Guide to Tejano and Regional Mexican Music]]'', Ramiro Burr felt that the lyrics, about \"finding the strength to walk away\", evoked \"the pain of love and the tone of redemption\".{{sfn|Burr|1999|p=189}} The song became an \"instant classic\", according to Roger Burns, writing in ''Icons of Latino America''.{{sfn|Burns|2008|p=465}} Other reviewers agreed that it was one of the most successful singles from ''Amor Prohibido'',{{sfn|Stavans|Augenbraum|2005|p=91}}{{sfn|Velasquez|2010}}<ref name=\"Onet.pl\">{{cite news|title=16. rocznica \u015bmierci Seleny |url=http://muzyka.onet.pl/10172,2261481,newsy.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320023923/http://muzyka.onet.pl/10172,2261481,newsy.html |archivedate=March 20, 2012 |newspaper=[[Onet.pl]] |date=31 March 2011 |accessdate=14 April 2011 |language=Polish |url-status=dead }}</ref> with Lisa Leal of [[KVTV]] commenting that the song is a Spanish-language counterpart of [[the Beatles]]' 1965 single \"[[Yesterday (Beatles song)|Yesterday]]\" in fan popularity.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Leal|first1=Lisa|title=Fans pay tribute to fallen Tejano Star Selena|url=http://www.kztv10.com/story/28677490/fans-pay-tribute-to-fallen-tejano-star-selena|website=[[KVTV|KVTV.com]]|accessdate=19 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180404175954/http://www.kztv10.com/story/28677490/fans-pay-tribute-to-fallen-tejano-star-selena|archive-date=April 4, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe track received several awards and accolades. It was the Song of the Year at the 1995 [[Broadcast Music, Inc.|Broadcast Music Awards]],<ref name=\"Songoftheyear\">{{cite journal|year=1997 |title=''Billboard'' Latin Awards |journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |volume= |issue= |pages=138 |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AQoEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA85&dq=Kat+DeLuna+No+Me+Queda+Mas#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=14 April 2011 }}</ref> and Vela received the Songwriter of the Year award in 1996.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Burr|first1=Ramiro|title=Pete Astudillo Leads BMI Latin Music Awards|journal=Billboard|date=May 18, 1996|volume=108|issue=20|pages=4, 68|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uA0EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=RA1-PA68&vq=no%20me%20queda%20mas&dq=bmi%20latin%20awards%201996%20intitle%3Abillboard&pg=RA1-PA68#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=8 July 2016}}</ref> Its video was honored as the Music Video of the Year at the 1995 [[Billboard Latin Music Awards|''Billboard'' Latin Music Awards]].<ref name=\"latinmusicawards\">{{cite news|title=''Billboard'', Univision present awards|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=ST&s_site=dfw&p_multi=ST&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAF9009A9E2EBDA&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]|date=9 June 1995|url-access=subscription }}</ref><ref name=\"musicvideo\">{{cite journal |author= |year=1995 |title=And The Latin Music Awards Goes To&nbsp;. |journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |volume=107 |issue=23 |pages=112 |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |doi= |pmid= |pmc= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0QsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA54&dq=no+me+queda+mas#v=onepage&q=no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false |accessdate=14 April 2011 }}</ref> \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" was ranked as the ninth-best Tejano song of all time on Ramiro Burr's top-ten list.{{sfn|Burr|1999|p=229}} It has appeared on several critics' \"best Selena songs\" lists, including [[BuzzFeed]] (at number one),<ref name=brain>{{cite web|last1=Galindo|first1=Brain|title=Ranking The 15 Greatest Selena Songs Ever|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/briangalindo/ranking-the-15-greatest-selena-songs-ever#13h00pr|website=[[BuzzFeed]]|publisher=BuzzFeed Inc|accessdate=October 1, 2014}}</ref> ''Latino Post'' (number four),<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sim\u00f3n|first1=Yara|title=Selena Day 2014: Countdown of Selena's Top 5 Songs|url=http://www.latinopost.com/articles/5586/20140415/selena-day-2014-countdown-of-selenas-top-5-songs.htm|website=Latino Post|accessdate=August 20, 2015}}</ref> and ''[[Latina (magazine)|Latina]]'' (number five).<ref name=latina>{{cite web|last1=Rodriguez|first1=Priscillia|title=Remembering Selena: Her Top Ten Songs|url=http://www.latina.com/music/selena-quintanilla-hit-songs-videos#5|website=Latina|publisher=Lauren Michaels|accessdate=October 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n''Billboard'' announced that a new airplay-measuring system for its music charts would be based on [[Nielsen rating]]s beginning on November 12, 1994.<ref name=newsystem>{{cite journal|last1=Lannert|first1=John|title=Hot Latin Songs > November 4, 1994|journal=Billboard|date=November 4, 1994|volume=106|issue=45|page=46|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YwgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA46&dq=Selena#v=onepage&q=Selena&f=false|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref> \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" entered the US [[Hot Latin Songs]] chart at number 40 on that date, and Selena's \"[[Bidi Bidi Bom Bom]]\" remained at number one.<ref name=newsystem/> On November 19, the song rose to number ten on that chart and subsequently debuted on the US [[Regional Mexican Airplay]] chart at number seven.<ref name=\"nov19\">{{cite journal|title=Hot Latin Songs > November 19, 1994|journal=Billboard|date=November 19, 1994|volume=106|issue=46|page=50|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZggEAAAAMBAJ&dq=billboard&q=no+me+queda+mas#v=snippet&q=no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016|author1=Nielsen Business Media|first1=Inc}}</ref> The following week, it climbed to the fifth and fourth positions on the Hot Latin Songs and Regional Mexican Airplay charts, respectively.<ref name=\"nov26\">{{cite journal|last1=Lannert|first1=John|title=Latin Notas|journal=Billboard|date=November 26, 1994|volume=106|issue=48|page=62|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aggEAAAAMBAJ&dq=billboard&q=no+me+queda+mas#v=snippet&q=no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref> ''Billboard'' contributor John Lannert, noting that three different songs had topped the Hot Latin Songs chart since the inception of the Nielsen-rating system, predicted that [[Luis Miguel]]'s number one single \"La Media Vuelta\" could be unseated by \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\".<ref name=\"nov26\"/> The following week, \"La Media Vuelta\" remained atop the chart and \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" rose to number two.<ref name=\"dec3\">{{cite journal|title=Hot Latin Songs > December 3, 1994|journal=Billboard|date=December 3, 1994|volume=106|issue=49|page=38|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZwgEAAAAMBAJ&dq=billboard&q=no+me+queda+mas#v=snippet&q=no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref> \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" topped the Regional Mexican Airplay chart for three consecutive weeks beginning on December 3, Selena's first number one on that chart.<ref name=\"dec3\"/><ref name=\"dec24\">{{cite journal|title=Regional Mexican Airplay > December 24, 1994|journal=Billboard|date=December 24, 1994|volume=106|issue=52|page=57|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZAgEAAAAMBAJ&dq=billboard&q=no+me+queda+mas#v=snippet&q=no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016|author1=Nielsen Business Media|first1=Inc}}</ref> The song peaked at number one on the Hot Latin Songs chart on December 17, her third consecutive number one.<ref name=\"dec17\">{{cite journal|title=Hot Latin Songs > December 17, 1994|journal=Billboard|date=December 17, 1994|volume=106|issue=50|page=25|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/90s/1994/BB-1994-12-17.pdf|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref> It debuted at number 13 on the US [[Latin Pop Songs]] chart on January 7, 1995, remaining atop the Hot Latin Songs chart.<ref name=\"jan7\">{{cite journal|title=Hot Latin Songs > January 7, 1995|journal=Billboard|date=January 7, 1995|volume=107|issue=1|page=29|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ugsEAAAAMBAJ&dq=billboard&q=no+me+queda+mas#v=snippet&q=no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016|author1=Nielsen Business Media|first1=Inc}}</ref> The song reclaimed the number-one spot on the Regional Mexican Airplay chart for January 14, unseating [[La Mafia]]'s \"Me Duele Estar Solo\".<ref name=\"jan14\">{{cite journal|title=Hot Latin Songs > January 14, 1995|journal=Billboard|date=January 14, 1995|volume=107|issue=2|page=29|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tQsEAAAAMBAJ&dq=billboard&q=no+me+queda+mas#v=snippet&q=no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016|author1=Nielsen Business Media|first1=Inc}}</ref> La Mafia displaced \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" from the top of the Regional Mexican Airplay and Hot Latin Songs charts on January 21, ending the song's five-week reign on the latter.<ref name=\"jan21\">{{cite journal|last1=Lannert|first1=John|title=Latin Notas|journal=Billboard|date=January 21, 1995|volume=107|issue=3|pages=37, 38|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uAsEAAAAMBAJ&dq=billboard&q=no+me+queda+mas#v=snippet&q=no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"jan21\"/> The following week, \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" regained the top of both charts.<ref name=\"jan28\">{{cite journal|title=Hot Latin Songs > January 28, 1995|journal=Billboard|date=January 28, 1995|volume=107|issue=4|page=39|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sgsEAAAAMBAJ&dq=billboard&q=no+me+queda+mas#v=snippet&q=no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016|author1=Nielsen Business Media|first1=Inc}}</ref> On February 4, it fell to number two on the Regional Mexican Airplay chart and retained the top spot on the Hot Latin Songs chart for its seventh nonconsecutive week.<ref name=\"feb4\">{{cite journal|title=Hot Latin Songs > February 4, 1995|journal=Billboard|date=February 4, 1995|volume=107|issue=5|page=43|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sAsEAAAAMBAJ&dq=billboard&q=no+me+queda+mas#v=snippet&q=no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016|author1=Nielsen Business Media|first1=Inc}}</ref> It was displaced from the top of the Hot Latin Songs chart on February 11 by [[Grupo Bronco]]'s \"Que No Me Olvide\".<ref name=\"feb11\">{{cite journal|title=Hot Latin Songs > February 11, 1995|journal=Billboard|date=February 11, 1995|volume=107|issue=6|page=35|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yAsEAAAAMBAJ&dq=billboard&q=no+me+queda+mas#v=snippet&q=no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016|author1=Nielsen Business Media|first1=Inc}}</ref> It was the most popular song from ''Amor Prohibido'' on Mexican radio.{{sfn|Perone|2012|p=84}}\n\nSelena was [[murder of Selena|shot and killed]] on March 31, 1995 by [[Yolanda Sald\u00edvar]], a friend who was the former manager of the singer's [[Selena Etc.]] boutiques.<ref name=\"Bitch\">{{cite news|title=October 12, 1995, the testimony of Norma Martinez |url=http://www.chron.com/content/chronicle/metropolitan/selena/transcripts/95/10/12/martinez.html |accessdate=September 27, 2015 |work=[[Houston Chronicle]] |date=October 12, 1995 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070715183634/http://www.chron.com/content/chronicle/metropolitan/selena/transcripts/95/10/12/martinez.html |archivedate=July 15, 2007 }}</ref> Four of her singles\u2014\"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\", \"Bidi Bidi Bom Bom\", \"[[Como la Flor]]\" and \"[[Amor Prohibido (song)|Amor Prohibido]]\"\u2014reentered the ''Billboard'' Hot Latin Songs and Regional Mexican Airplay charts on April 15.<ref name=posthumous>{{cite journal|last1=Lannert|first1=John|title=Latin Notas|journal=Billboard|date=15 April 1995|volume=107|issue=15|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7wsEAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=Selena&f=false|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref> \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" placed fifth and eighth on the Hot Latin Songs and Regional Mexican Airplay charts, respectively,<ref name=\"posthumous\"/> and remained in the top ten of the Hot Latin Songs chart for 12 consecutive weeks.<ref name=\"ju1\">{{cite journal|title=Hot Latin Tracks > July 1, 1995|journal=Billboard|date=July 1, 1995|volume=107|issue=26|page=37|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rgsEAAAAMBAJ&dq=billboard&q=no+me+queda+mas#v=snippet&q=no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016|author1=Nielsen Business Media|first1=Inc}}</ref> ''Billboard'' posthumously named Selena the Top Latin Artist of the 1990s in recognition of her fourteen top-ten singles on the Hot Latin Songs chart, including seven number ones.<ref name=\"selena\">{{cite journal| last = Mayfield| first = Geoff| date = December 26, 1999| title = Totally '90s: Diary of a Decade| journal = Billboard| publisher = Nielsen Business Media, Inc.| volume = 111\n| issue = 52| page = YE-16| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=9w0EAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=latin&f=false| accessdate =March 30, 2010}}</ref> \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" was the [[Billboard Top Latin Songs Year-End Chart|most successful US Latin single of 1995]].<ref name=\"billboardmag\">\n{{Cite journal\n| date = November 28, 1998\n| title = Topping The Charts Year By Year\n| journal = Billboard\n| volume = 110\n| issue = 48\n| page = LMQ3\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=MAoEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA38&dq=rudy+la+scala&cd=1#v=onepage&q=rudy%20la%20scala\n| accessdate =March 3, 2010| author1 =\nNielsen Business Media| first1 =\nInc}}</ref><ref name=\"numberonesingles\">{{cite news |title=Remembering Selena's Trailblazing Music |author=Rivas, Jorge |url=http://colorlines.com/archives/2011/03/16th_anniversary_of_selenas_death.html |newspaper=Colorlines |date=March 31, 2011 |accessdate=April 14, 2011}}</ref> It ranked eleventh on ''Billboard''{{'}}s quarter-century celebration of the Hot Latin Songs chart in 2011.<ref name=\"hotlatinartists\"/> ''Billboard'' began monitoring [[music download|digital downloads]] of Latin songs during the week ending January 23, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Latin Digital Songs > January 23, 2010|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2010-01-23/latin-digital-songs|website=Billboard.biz|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=April 14, 2016}}</ref> \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" made its debut at number 23 on the [[Latin Digital Songs]] chart following the twentieth anniversary of Selena's death.<ref>{{cite web|title=Latin Digital Songs > April 18, 2015|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2015-04-18/latin-digital-songs|website=Billboard.biz|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref> On the [[Billboard charts#Latin|Latin Pop Digital Songs]] chart, the song debuted at number 22 and peaked at number nine.<ref>{{cite web|title=Latin Pop Digital > April 11, 2015|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2015-04-11/latin-pop-digital-songs|website=Billboard.biz|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nAn accompanying music video for \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" was filmed in October 1994 at the [[San Antonio]] [[San Antonio station (Texas)|Amtrak station]].<ref name=\"production\">{{cite journal|last1=Bessman|first1=Jim|title=Production Notes|journal=Billboard|date=November 12, 1994|volume=106|issue=46|page=38|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aAgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA38&dq=Selena+No+Me+Queda+Mas#v=onepage&q=Selena%20No%20Me%20Queda%20Mas&f=false|accessdate=25 May 2016}}</ref> Produced by Summit Productions, the video was directed by Sean Roberts.<ref name=\"production\"/> Shooting took four days to complete.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=128}} Jack Morgan was the on-set photographer, and Diego Aguilar produced the video.<ref name=\"production\"/> Selena wore the same dress that she did when she won a [[Grammy Award for Best Mexican/Mexican-American Album|Grammy Award for Best Mexican/American Album]] in [[36th Grammy Awards|1994]].{{sfn|Arrar\u00e1s|1997|p=34}} Veronica Flores, a reporter for the ''San Antonio Express-News'', was asked to make a cameo appearance as a wedding guest.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Flores|first1=Veronica|title=My short, happy friendship with Selena|url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/news/article/My-short-happy-friendship-with-Selena-1646173.php|accessdate=19 April 2016|work=San Antonio Express-News|date=March 25, 2005}}</ref> American model Freddie Martinez portrayed Selena's love interest after auditioning for the role in San Antonio.<ref>{{cite news|title=Selena: Her Voice Will Never Be Silenced|url=http://www.caller.com/entertainment/selena/selena-her-voice-will-never-be-silenced-ep-1039475785.html|accessdate=August 19, 2016|work=[[Corpus Christi Caller-Times]]|date=April 2, 1995}}</ref>\n\nThe video's location was later used for Selena's fashion-show scene in ''[[Selena (film)|Selena]]'' (1997), starring [[Jennifer Lopez]].<ref>{{cite AV media |people=[[Jennifer Lopez]], [[Edward James Olmos]], [[Jon Seda]], [[Jackie Guerra]] |date=March 21, 1997 |title=[[Selena (film)|Selena]] |type=DVD |time=127 minutes |publisher=[[Warner Bros.]] }}</ref> [[Hillary Clinton]] used \"Bidi Bidi Bom Bom\" as part of her [[Hillary Clinton presidential campaign, 2016|2016 presidential campaign]] in San Antonio (which received a mixed response from Hispanics),<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gamboa|first1=Suzanne|title=Hillary Clinton and The 'Abuela' Factor|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/hillary-clinton-abuela-factor-n485226|accessdate=13 April 2016|work=[[NBC News]]|date=December 24, 2015}}</ref> playing the song at the location where Selena recorded the music video for \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Reichard|first1=Raquel|title=Clinton Enters \"Latinos for Hillary\" event in Texas With Selena's 'Bidi Bidi Bom Bom'|url=http://www.latina.com/lifestyle/politics/hillary-clinton-event-selena-bidi-bidi-bom-bom|accessdate=13 April 2016|work=Latina|date=October 16, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426210518/http://www.latina.com/lifestyle/politics/hillary-clinton-event-selena-bidi-bidi-bom-bom|archivedate=April 26, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Univision]] ranked the music video at number four on their top ten favorite music videos of Selena.<ref>{{cite news|title=El Top Ten de los videos de Selena Quintanilla |url=http://www.univision.com/musica/el-top-ten-de-los-videos-de-selena-quintanilla |trans-title=The Top Ten Videos of Selena Quintanilla |accessdate=June 9, 2016 |work=[[Univision]] |date=March 31, 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6i8vEM2Ev?url=http://www.univision.com/musica/el-top-ten-de-los-videos-de-selena-quintanilla |archivedate=June 9, 2016 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn the video, Selena is sitting in a restaurant where a mariachi band is performing. A waiter offers her a glass of water. As the singer enjoys her dinner, the waiter returns with a note saying that her lover (for whom she has been waiting) has left her for another woman. Selena takes a sip of water before she leaves the restaurant, crying.\n\nThe singer is in the dark behind a busy highway, sobbing and peeling petals off a white rose in a game of [[He loves me... he loves me not]] as a [[Montage (filmmaking)|montage]] is playing of images of Selena and her former lover. Selena then sings on a staircase in a white dress, accompanied by an orchestra. She considers crashing her ex-lover's beach wedding, but instead runs away in tears. Selena's ex-lover and his new wife kiss, and a video plays in which he kisses Selena's hands. He then embraces his wife as Selena looks down, sobbing.\n\n==Cover versions==\n{{Multiple image|left|image1=Kat DeLuna 2008-3 cropped.jpg|total_width=300|width1=319|height1=560|alt1=Kat DeLuna dancing onstage in a short, black dress|image2=Pepe Aguilar cropped.jpg|width2=250|height2=323|alt2=Pepe Aguilar singing onstage|footer=Dominican singer Kat DeLuna (left) and Mexican singer [[Pepe Aguilar]] have covered \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" in live performances.}}\nAmerican [[salsa music|salsa]] singer [[Tito Nieves]] recorded \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" for his third studio album, ''Un Tipo Comun'' (1996).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Estevez Jr|first1=Jose A.|title=Un Tip Comun > Album Review|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/un-tipo-comun-mw0000645468|website=AllMusic|publisher=Rovi Corporation|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref> The song was commercially more successful than the four singles released from the album, where it peaked at number seven on the US [[Tropical Songs]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=Awards > Un Tipo Comun|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/un-tipo-comun-mw0000645468/awards|website=AllMusic|publisher=Rovi Corporation|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref> That same year, Dominican singer [[Kat DeLuna]] won first place when she sang the song at the New Jersey Hispanic Youth Showcase, a children's singing competition.<ref>{{cite journal|title=I Want To Become A Singer|journal=[[Latina (magazine)|Latina]]|publisher=Latina Publications|date=April 2008|volume=12|issue=4|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sDIrAQAAIAAJ&q=Selena+No+Me+Queda+M%C3%A1s&dq=Selena+No+Me+Queda+M%C3%A1s|accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref> In 1998, [[Los Tres Reyes]] (a mariachi group produced by Abraham Quintanilla, Jr.) recorded a duet version of the song.<ref>{{cite news|last=Burr|first=Ramiro|title=Los Tres Reyes rekindle romantic classics for Mother's Day crowd|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SAEC&p_theme=saec&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAFE83D0869F0D8&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=San Antonio Express-News|date=12 May 1998|url-access=subscription }}</ref> [[Graciela Beltran]] covered the song during a memorial for Selena in [[Houston]] in 2003.<ref>{{cite news|title=The People's Queen' at the fair|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MSSB&p_theme=mssb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=102446A9B35A3CE0&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=[[The Merced Sun-Star]]|date=14 July 2003|url-access=subscription }}</ref> Mexican singer [[Pepe Aguilar]] performed and recorded \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" for a live, televised tribute concert, ''[[Selena \u00a1VIVE!]]'', in April 2005. According to Michael Clark of the ''[[Houston Chronicle]]'', \"[Aguilar's] vocal ... was reminiscent of [[Aaron Neville]]\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Clark|first=Michael|title=Modern, traditional mix in vibrant Selena tribute|url=http://www.chron.com/entertainment/music/article/Modern-traditional-mix-in-vibrant-Selena-tribute-1930189.php|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=[[Houston Chronicle]]|date=8 April 2005}}</ref>\n\nMexican pop group Palomo recorded \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\" for their [[live album]], ''En Concierto-En Vivo Desde L.A.'' (2005). The song debuted at number 37 on the Regional Mexican Airplay chart on March 19, 2005,<ref>{{cite journal|title=Regional Mexican Airplay > March 19, 2005|journal=Billboard|date=March 19, 2005|volume=117|issue=12|page=27|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=thQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA27&dq=Palomo+no+me+queda+mas#v=onepage&q=Palomo%20no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016|author1=Nielsen Business Media|first1=Inc}}</ref> and at number 46 on the Hot Latin Songs chart on April 2.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Hot Latin Songs > April 2, 2005|journal=Billboard|date=April 2, 2005|volume=117|issue=14|page=23|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_BMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA23&dq=Palomo+no+me+queda+mas#v=onepage&q=Palomo%20no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016|author1=Nielsen Business Media|first1=Inc}}</ref> It remained on the chart until July 16, peaking at numbers 19 and six on the Hot Latin Songs and Regional Mexican Airplay charts, respectively.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Hot Latin Songs > July 16, 2005|journal=Billboard|date=July 16, 2005|volume=117|issue=29|page=76|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uRQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA76&dq=Palomo+no+me+queda+mas#v=onepage&q=Palomo%20no%20me%20queda%20mas&f=false|accessdate=19 April 2016|author1=Nielsen Business Media|first1=Inc}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Chart history > Palomo|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/277178/palomo/chart?f=373|website=Billboard|accessdate=25 June 2016}}</ref> Ricky Vela received a BMI Latin Music Award for the Palomo's cover in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title=BMI Complete List of Winners|url=http://www.bmi.com/press/entry/534979|website=Broadcast Music, Inc.|accessdate=August 25, 2016}}</ref> American singer [[Jos\u00e9 Feliciano]] recorded it for his album, ''Jose Feliciano y Amigos'', in 2006; Ramiro Burr of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' called it a \"bittersweet ranchera\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Burr|first=Ramiro|title=Jose Feliciano teams up with friends on 'Amigos'|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2007-01-17/features/0701160309_1_jose-feliciano-raul-di-blasio-accordion|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=17 January 2007}}</ref> Cuban singer To\u00f1ita recorded the song for her album, ''Desafiando al Destino'', in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title=iTunes > Music > Desafinado al destino|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/desafiando-al-destino/id262298876|work=[[iTunes Store]]|publisher=[[Apple Inc]]|accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref> A year later, American singer Maria Williams recorded an English-language version entitled \"Nothing Left For Me\" for her debut album ''Hybrid''.<ref>{{cite web|title=iTunes > Music > Hybrid|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/hybrid/id295953087|work=iTunes Store|publisher=Apple Inc|accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref> American singer [[David Archuleta]] performed the song as a tribute to Selena at the [[2010 Tejano Music Awards]],<ref>{{Cite episode |title=2010 Tejano Music Awards |episodelink=2010 Tejano Music Awards |series=Tejano Music Awards |serieslink=Tejano Music Awards |network=Telemundo |airdate=July 20, 2010 |language=Spanish}}</ref> and [[Karen Rodriguez]] sang it during the [[American Idol (season 10)|tenth season]] of ''[[American Idol]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cruz Tejada|first=Miguel|title=La dominicana Karen Rodr\u00edguez a un paso de ser  la nueva estrella de American Idol|url=http://elnuevodiario.com.do/app/article.aspx?id=234618|work=El Nuevo Diario|accessdate=21 December 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421114307/http://elnuevodiario.com.do/app/article.aspx?id=234618|archivedate=April 21, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=de Moraes|first=Lisa|title='American Idol' 2011: Top 24 survive the Trail of Tears|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/tvblog/2011/02/american-idol-names-the-top-24.html|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=25 February 2010}}</ref> On May 1, 2015, Jennifer Lopez performed \"[[A Selena Tribute]]\" at the [[2015 Latin Billboard Music Awards]], which included \"No Me Queda M\u00e1s\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Emery|first1=Debby|title=Jennifer Lopez's Touching Tribute to Selena at Billboard Latin Music Awards|url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/entertainment/article/Jennifer-Lopez-s-Touching-Tribute-to-Selena-at-6235210.php|accessdate=20 September 2015|work=San Antonio Express-News|date=May 1, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304052635/http://www.mysanantonio.com/entertainment/article/Jennifer-Lopez-s-Touching-Tribute-to-Selena-at-6235210.php|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Lopez was praised by music critics, who appreciated the singer's Selena-esque costumes.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nessif|first1=Bruna|title=Jennifer Lopez Joins Los Dinos for Beautiful Selena Quintanilla-P\u00e9rez Tribute at 2015 Billboard Latin Music Awards|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/652379/jennifer-lopez-joins-los-dinos-for-beautiful-selena-quintanilla-perez-tribute-at-2015-billboard-latin-music-awards|website=E! News|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=de Valle|first1=Elaine|title=Jennifer Lopez Pays Tribute to Selena at Billboard Latin Music Awards|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/events/latin-awards/6553501/jennifer-lopez-selena-tribute-billboard-latin-music-awards|website=Billboard|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Flashback: Jennifer Lopez Pays Tribute to Slain Singer Selena|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/flashback-jennifer-lopez-pays-tribute-to-slain-singer-selena-20160331|accessdate=14 April 2016|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=March 31, 2016}}</ref> The recording debuted and peaked at number 33 on the Hot Latin Songs chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chart history > Jennifer Lopez|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/304444/jennifer-lopez/chart?f=363|website=Billboard|accessdate=25 June 2016}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Credits and personnel==\nCredits adapted from the [[liner notes]] of ''Amor Prohibido''.<ref name=\"albumnotes\"/>\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n*Selena&nbsp;\u2013 [[Singing|vocals]]\n*Joe Ojeda&nbsp;\u2013 [[keyboards]]\n*[[Ricky Vela]]&nbsp;\u2013 writer, [[keyboards]]\n*[[Chris P\u00e9rez]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[guitar]]s\n*[[A.B. Quintanilla III]]&nbsp;\u2013 arranger, producer\n*[[Bebu Silvetti]]&nbsp;\u2013 arranger\n*[[Suzette Quintanilla]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[drum kit|drums]]\n{{col-2}}\n*[[Arturo Meza]], Jesse \"O'Jay\" Martinez&nbsp;\u2013 [[percussion]]/[[conga]]s\n*Odalis Smith, Helen Stackhouse, Morgan Taylor&nbsp;\u2013 [[french horn]]\n*Gertrude Myers, Ruth Moore, John Foster, Alice Powell&nbsp;\u2013 [[violin]]\n*Lucy Richardson&nbsp;\u2013 [[cello]]\n*Francisca Malorie, James Watson&nbsp;\u2013 [[flute]]\n*Edward Jackson, Jose Deluna&nbsp;\u2013 [[trumpet]]\n*Freddie Corea, Don Shelton&nbsp;\u2013 [[tambourine]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"|Chart (1994)\n! scope=\"col\"|Peak<br>position\n|-\n!scope=row{{singlechart|Billboardlatinsongs|1|artist=Selena|id={{BillboardID|Selena}}}}\n|-\n!scope=row{{singlechart|Billboardregionalmexican|1|artist=Selena|id={{BillboardID|Selena}}}}\n|-\n!scope=row{{singlechart|Billboardlatinpopsongs|13|artist=Selena|id={{BillboardID|Selena}}}}\n|-\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"|Chart (1995)\n! scope=\"col\"|Position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|US Hot Latin Songs (''Billboard'')<ref>{{cite journal|title=Year-End Charts, ''Billboard''|journal=Billboard|date=28 November 1998|volume=110|issue=48|pages=104|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MAoEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA38|accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|US Regional Mexican Airplay (''Billboard'')<ref name=\"yearend95\">{{cite journal|title=1995 Year In Music|journal=Billboard|date=December 23, 1995|volume=107|issue=51|page=33|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nQ0EAAAAMBAJ|accessdate=May 12, 2015}}</ref>\n|2\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n===All-time charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\