omacy: With Special Reference to England and Germany, 1890\u20131914'' (1940) [https://www.questia.com/library/1023289/publicity-and-diplomacy-with-special-reference-to online]\n* Jowett, Garth S. & Victoria O'Donnell. ''Propaganda and Persuasion'', 6th edn. California: Sage Publications, 2014. A detailed overview of the history, function, and analyses of propaganda.\n* Lohrey, Andrew, ed. ''Taking the Risk out of Democracy: Corporate Propaganda versus Freedom and Liberty''. Urbana, Ill.: University of Illinois Press, 1997.\n* [[Randal Marlin|Marlin, Randal]]. ''Propaganda & The Ethics of Persuasion''. Orchard Park, New York: Broadview Press, 2002.\n* McCombs, M. E. & D. L. Shaw. \u201cThe agenda-setting function of mass media\u201d, ''Public Opinion Quarterly'' 36, no. 2 (1972): 176\u2013187.\n* Moran, T. \"Propaganda as Pseudocommunication\", ''Et Cetera'' 2 (1979): 181\u2013197.\n* Nelson, Richard Allen. ''A Chronology and Glossary of Propaganda in the United States''. Westport, Conn.: Greenwood Press, 1996.\n* Pratkanis, Anthony & Elliot Aronson. ''Age of Propaganda: The Everyday Use and Abuse of Persuasion''. New York: W.H. Freeman and Company, 1992.\n* Rutherford, Paul, ''Endless Propaganda: The Advertising of Public Goods''. Toronto: University of Toronto Press. (2000)\n* Rutherford, Paul, ''Weapons of Mass Persuasion: Marketing the War Against Iraq''. Toronto: University of Toronto Press, 2004.\n* Shanahan, James, ed. ''Propaganda without Propagandists? Six Case Studies in U.S. Propaganda''. Hampton Press, 2001.\n* Shaw Jeffrey M., ''Illusions of Freedom: Thomas Merton and Jacques Ellul on Technology and the Human Condition''. Eugene, OR: Wipf and Stock. {{ISBN|978-1625640581}} (2014)\n* {{cite book|editor=|title=Propaganda and American Democracy|last=Snow|first=Nancy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sOjYAgAAQBAJ|date=10 March 2014|location=Baton Rouge|pages=|publisher=LSU Press|isbn=978-0-8071-5415-1}}\n* {{cite book|last=Snow|first=Nancy|authorlink=Nancy Snow (academic)|title=Propaganda, Inc.: Selling America's Culture to the World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LfYPpXW9Bf4C|date=4 January 2011|location=New York|pages=|publisher=Seven Stories Press|isbn=978-1-60980-082-6}}\n* Sproule J. Michael, ''Channels of Propaganda''. Bloomington, IN: EDINFO Press. (1994)\n* {{cite book | last=Stanley |first=Jason |authorlink=Jason Stanley | title=How Propaganda Works |year=2016 |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn=978-0691173429}}\n* Stauber, John & Sheldon Rampton. ''Toxic Sludge Is Good for You! Lies, Damn Lies and the Public Relations Industry''. Monroe, Maine: Common Courage Press, 1995.\n\n===Essays and articles===\n* [[John H. Brown (scholar)|Brown, John H.]]. \"[https://www.uscpublicdiplomacy.org/blog/two-ways-looking-propaganda Two Ways of Looking at Propaganda]\" (2006)\n* Garcia, Hugo. [https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/13619462.2019.1571920 \"Reluctant liars? Public debates on propaganda and democracy in twentieth-century Britain (ca. 1914\u20131950)\"], ''[[Contemporary British History]]'', vol. 33, no. 3 (2019), pp. 383\u2013404.\n* Kosar, Kevin R., [https://fas.org/sgp/crs/misc/RL32750.pdf Public Relations and Propaganda: Restrictions on Executive Branch Activities], CRS Report RL32750, February 2005.\n\n{{Commons}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Disinformation}}\n\n{{Propaganda}}\n{{Media manipulation}}\n{{Philosophical logic}}\n{{Psychological manipulation}}\n{{Conformity}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Propaganda| ]]\n[[Category:Barriers to critical thinking]]\n[[Category:Deception]]\n[[Category:Political communication]]\n[[Category:Psychological manipulation]]\n[[Category:Public opinion]]\n", "name_user": "Darren1515", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Propaganda"}
{"title_page": "Yvette Nicole Brown", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Yvette Nicole Brown\n| image              = Yvette Nicole Brown by Gage Skidmore 5.jpg\n| caption            = Brown in July 2019\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1971|08|12}} \n| birth_place        = [[East Cleveland, Ohio]], U.S.\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Akron]]\n| occupation         = Actress, voice actress, comedian, writer\n| years_active       = 1992\u2013present\n| website            = {{URL|yvettenicolebrown.com}}\n}}\n'''Yvette Nicole Brown''' (born August 12, 1971) is an American actress, voice actress, and host. Brown has appeared in numerous commercials, television shows, and films throughout her career. She starred as [[Shirley Bennett]] on the [[National Broadcasting Company|NBC]] comedy series ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]''. Her voice on community was so shrill, facetious and juvenile it is rumored multiple actors including Chevy Chase attempted suicide via ball point pen directly to the ear canal. The attempts failed and had no bearing on the character. She somehow become even worse and nothing made fans happier than when Shirley was finally axed from the show. She had a recurring role on the [[Nickelodeon]] sitcom ''[[Drake & Josh]]'' as Helen Dubois, and voiced the character Cookie on the American-Canadian animated series ''[[Pound Puppies (2010 TV series)|Pound Puppies]]''. Brown also starred as Dani in the 2015 version of ''[[The Odd Couple (2015 TV series)|The Odd Couple]]'' on [[CBS]] and as Dina Rose on the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] sitcom ''[[The Mayor (TV series)|The Mayor]]''. In 2018, she assumed the role of Nora, AA sponsor to Christy, the central character on ''[[Mom (TV series)|Mom]]''.\n\nBrown has also had guest roles in television shows such as ''[[That '70s Show]]'', ''[[The Office (American TV series)|The Office]]'', ''[[Boston Legal]]'', ''[[Chuck (TV series)|Chuck]]'', and ''[[The Soul Man]]''. In addition to television, she has had supporting roles in films such as ''[[(500) Days of Summer]]'', ''[[Tropic Thunder]]'', ''[[Repo Men]]'', and ''[[Percy Jackson: Sea of Monsters]]''. She also voiced \"Harper\" from the video game ''[[Minecraft: Story Mode]]'' in addition to Cookie on ''[[Pound Puppies]]'', Luna on ''[[Elena of Avalor]]'' and Principal [[Amanda Waller]] on ''[[DC Super Hero Girls]]'' She has hosted [[Syfy]] [[cosplay]] series ''[[Cosplay Melee]]'' and has been a frequent couch guest on ''[[Talking Dead]]''. She has also served as a guest co-host on talk shows including ''[[The View (talk show)|The View]]'', ''[[The Talk (talk show)|The Talk]]'', ''[[The Real (talk show)|The Real]]'' and ''[[The Jeff Probst Show]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nYvette Nicole Brown was born on August 12, 1971, in [[East Cleveland, Ohio]].<ref name=IMDb>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1304328/|title=Yvette Nicole Brown|publisher=IMDb}}</ref> She graduated from [[Warrensville Heights High School]] in 1989. Brown studied [[communication studies]] at the [[University of Akron]] and graduated with her Bachelor of Arts in Communication in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uakron.edu/im/online-newsroom/news_details.dot?newsId=1365607&crumbTitle=%27Community%27%20star%20Yvette%20Nicole%20Brown%20to%20be%20honored%20by%20UA|title=''Community'' star Yvette Nicole Brown to be honored by UA|date=August 31, 2010|publisher=The University of Akron}}</ref><ref name=UofAkron>{{cite web|url=http://www.uakron.edu/race/keynote/yvette-nicole-brown.dot|title=Yvette Nicole Brown|publisher=The University of Akron}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduating, Brown took acting classes in [[Hollywood]], [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"Cleveland\">{{cite news|last=Dawidziak|first=Mark|work=[[The Plain Dealer]]|title=Yvette Nicole Brown, an East Cleveland native, enjoys role on TV sitcom ''Community''|url= http://www.cleveland.com/tv/index.ssf/2009/11/yvette_nicole_brown_an_east_cl.html|date=November 13, 2009|accessdate=April 26, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nBrown appeared as \"Yvette\" in the music video \"1-4-All-4-1\" by the East Coast Family, a [[Michael Bivins]] project, for [[Biv10 Records]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xlZv2cpLReM YouTube: East Coast Family 1-4-All-4-1] | Retrieved 11-20-2011 | 2:22 mark</ref> Brown said of the experience, \"It was a great run, but I guess music was just never meant to be for me.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Bierly|first=Mandi|title='Community': Get to know Yvette Nicole Brown (and how she got to know Chevy, Joel, Jude, and Gerard)|url=https://ew.com/article/2009/09/24/community-yvette-nicole-brown-chevy-joel/|website=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=October 4, 2019|date=September 24, 2009}}</ref>\n\nBrown first appeared on commercials before entering television shows and films a few years later.<ref name=\"Wash\">{{cite news|last=Asim|first=Jabari|work=[[The Washington Post]]|title=The 'Trouble' With Black Actresses|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/08/06/AR2006080600806.html|date=August 6, 2006|accessdate=April 26, 2010}}</ref> She has since played roles on television shows such as ''[[The War at Home (TV series)|The War at Home]]'', ''[[Malcolm in the Middle]]'', ''[[That's So Raven]]'', and the American version of ''[[The Office (American TV series)|The Office]]''. She also had a recurring role as movie theater manager [[Helen Dubois]] in the [[Nickelodeon]] sitcom ''[[Drake & Josh]]''. Brown reprised the role in the season 2 episode of ''[[Victorious]]'' titled \"Helen Back Again\".<ref name=\"Cleveland\" /> She also provided the voice of Cookie on [[Hub Network|The Hub]]'s ''[[Pound Puppies (2010 TV series)|Pound Puppies]]''.\n\nIn 2009, Brown began starring as [[Shirley Bennett]] on the comedy series ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]''. On September 30, 2014, Brown announced that she would be leaving the show after five seasons in order to take care of her ailing father. In her announcement she said, \"My dad needs daily care and he needs me. The idea of being away 16 hours a day for five months, I couldn't do it. It was a difficult decision for me to make, but I had to choose my dad.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Schneider |first=Michael |url=http://www.tvguide.com/News/Yvette-Nicole-Brown-1087724.aspx?rss=news&partnerid=spi&profileid=05 |title=Exclusive: Yvette Nicole Brown Departs ''Community'' |work=[[TV Guide]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=September 30, 2014 |accessdate=October 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\nShe has appeared in television commercials for [[Hamburger Helper]], [[Big Lots]], [[Pine-Sol]], [[Comcast]], [[Aquapod (bottle)|Aquapod]], Shout, Fiber One, [[Yoplait]] Yogurt, [[DiGiorno|DiGiorno Pizza]], [[Dairy Queen]], and [[Time Warner]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}} She has appeared on episodes of ''[[The Thrilling Adventure Hour]]'' as \"The Troubleshooter\" in the ''Sparks Nevada, Marshall on Mars'' series.\n\nIn 2012, Brown appeared as a celebrity contestant on [[Game Show Network|GSN]]'s ''[[Pyramid (game show)|The Pyramid]]'' with her ''Community'' co-star [[Danny Pudi]].\n\nIn 2014, it was reported that Brown was set to recur on the [[USA Network]] series ''[[Benched]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dawidziak|first1=Mark|title=Molly Shannon and Yvette Nicole Brown courted for USA Network's 'Benched'|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tv-blog/index.ssf/2014/06/molly_shannon_and_yvette_nicole_brown_courted_for_usa_networks_benched.html|website=cleveland.com|accessdate=17 June 2014}}</ref> Shortly after her exit of ''Community'', Brown's role of Dani on the [[CBS]] sitcom ''[[The Odd Couple (2015 TV series)|The Odd Couple]]'' was upgraded to series regular.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2014/10/04/yvette-nicole-brown-the-odd-couple-series-regular-cbs/|title=CBS' Odd Couple Reboot Promotes Yvette Nicole Brown to Series Regular|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|work=TV Line|date=October 4, 2014|accessdate=October 5, 2014}}</ref> She has also been a regular guest on AMC's ''[[Talking Dead]]''. She currently hosts [[Syfy]] [[cosplay]] series ''[[Cosplay Melee]]''.\n\nIn July 2018, Brown temporarily replaced [[Chris Hardwick]] as the host of ''Talking Dead'' and served as moderator for ''[[The Walking Dead (TV series)|The Walking Dead]]'' and ''[[Fear the Walking Dead]]'' panels at the [[San Diego Comic-Con]] during Hardwick's suspension.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/yvette-nicole-brown-replace-chris-hardwick-walking-dead-200343502.html|title=Yvette Nicole Brown to Replace Chris Hardwick as \u2018Walking Dead\u2019 Panel Moderator at Comic-Con|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Brown wrote the independent feature ''Always a Bridesmaid'', a romantic comedy. Set for a fall release, the film stars [[Jordan Calloway]] and Javicia Leslie, and features Marcel Spears, [[Brandon Micheal Hall]], [[Affion Crockett]], [[Richard Lawson (actor)|Richard Lawson]], and [[Telma Hopkins]] among the supporting cast.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/yvette-nicole-brown-always-a-bridesmaid-movie-1202597771/|title=Yvette Nicole Brown To Make Screenwriting Debut With \u2018Always A Bridesmaid\u2019|last=N'Duka|first=Amanda|last2=N'Duka|first2=Amanda|date=2019-04-19|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-06-29}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n===Politics===\n[[File:Elizabeth Warren & Yvette Nicole Brown (49548977053).jpg|thumb|Brown campaigning with Elizabeth Warren]]\nBrown endorsed and campaigned for [[Elizabeth Warren]] in the [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mobilize.us/nevadaforwarren/event/235065/ |website=mobilize.us |accessdate=February 15, 2020 |title=Women with Warren: Coffee and Chat with Yvette Nicole Brown |date=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''His Woman, His Wife''\n| \n|\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''180 Miles Away''\n| Other woman\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Little Black Book]]''\n| Production assistant\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2005\n| ''{{sortname|The|Island|dab=2005 film}}''\n| Harvest Nurse\n|\n|-\n| ''{{sortname|The|Kid & I}}''\n| Bunny\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Dreamgirls (film)|Dreamgirls]]''\n| Curtis' secretary\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''{{sortname|The|Neighbor|nolink=1}}''\n| Receptionist\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2008\n| ''[[Meet Dave]]''\n| [[Old Navy]] saleswoman\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Tropic Thunder]]''\n| Vivica (Peck's assistant)\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=4| 2009\n| ''N.C.B.S''\n| Flashback wife\n| Short film\n|-\n| ''[[Hotel for Dogs (film)|Hotel for Dogs]]''\n| Ms. Camwell\n|\n|-\n| ''[[500 Days of Summer]]''\n| New secretary\n|\n|-\n| ''{{sortname|The|Ugly Truth}}''\n| Dori\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Repo Men]]''\n| Rhodesia\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Percy Jackson: Sea of Monsters]]''\n| Gray Sister #2\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Yellowbird (film)|Yellowbird]]''\n| Ladybug (voice)\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Smartass]]''\n| Officer Neesy\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=3| 2019\n| ''[[Avengers: Endgame]]''\n| S.H.I.E.L.D. Agent\n| \n|-\n| ''Always a Bridesmaid''\n| Pastor Althea Brody\n| Also writer and executive producer\n|-\n| ''[[Lady and the Tramp (2019 film)|Lady and the Tramp]]''\n| Aunt Sarah\n| \n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Broken Diamonds]]''\n| Cookie\n| ''completed''\n|-\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2002\n| ''[[For the People (2002 TV series)|For the People]]''\n| Server\n| Episode: \"Lonely Hearts\"\n|-\n| ''[[Do Over]]''\n| Woman\n| Episode: \"Investing in the Future\"\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[Girlfriends (2000 TV series)|Girlfriends]]''\n| Sherri Childs\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n|rowspan=4| 2004\n| ''[[Curb Your Enthusiasm]]''\n| Stewardess\n| Episode: \"[[Opening Night (Curb Your Enthusiasm)|Opening Night]]\"\n|-\n| ''{{sortname|The|Big House|dab=2004 TV series}}''\n| Eartha Cleveland\n| 6 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Two and a Half Men]]''\n| Mandy\n| Episode: \"[[Just Like Buffalo]]\"\n|-\n| ''[[7th Heaven (TV series)|7th Heaven]]''\n| Leah Morris\n| Episode: \"Gratitude\"\n|-\n| 2004\u201307\n| ''[[Drake & Josh]]''\n| [[Helen Dubois]]\n| 15 episodes\n|-\n|rowspan=4| 2005\n| ''[[Fat Actress]]''\n| Woman in restaurant\n| Episode: \"Big Butts\"\n|-\n| ''[[That's So Raven]]''\n| Monica\n| Episode: \"[[Too Much Pressure (That's So Raven)|Too Much Pressure]]\"\n|-\n| ''[[That '70s Show]]''\n| Sgt. Davis\n| Episode: \"[[You're My Best Friend (That '70s Show)|You're My Best Friend]]\"\n|-\n| ''[[Hot Properties (TV series)|Hot Properties]]''\n| Oprah-Head\n| Episode: \"Waiting for Oprah\"\n|-\n|rowspan=6| 2006\n| ''[[Malcolm in the Middle]]''\n| Female security agent #2\n| Episode: \"Bride of Ida\"\n|-\n| ''[[House (TV series)|House]]''\n| Ellen Stambler\n| Episode: \"[[Sex Kills]]\"\n|-\n| ''{{sortname|The|War at Home|dab=TV series}}''\n| Airport security\n| Episode: \"The West Palm Beach Story\"\n|-\n| ''[[Half & Half]]''\n| Ceci\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Pepper Dennis]]''\n| Angela Howell\n| Episode: \"Pepper Dennis Behind Bars\"\n|-\n| ''[[Sleeper Cell (TV series)|Sleeper Cell]]''\n| Fatima\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n|rowspan=5| 2007\n| ''{{sortname|The|Office|dab=American TV series}}''\n| Paris\n| Episode: \"[[The Return (The Office)|The Return]]\"\n|-\n| ''{{sortname|The|Loop|dab=American TV series}}''\n| Isabelle Miller\n| Episode: \"Yeah, Presents\"\n|-\n| ''[[American Body Shop]]''\n| Ms. Durant\n| Episode: \"Pilot\"\n|-\n| ''[[Entourage (American TV series)|Entourage]]''\n| ''[[Daily Variety]]'' agent\n| Episode: \"[[Gary's Desk]]\"\n|-\n| ''[[Boston Legal]]''\n| Doris Thumper\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n|rowspan=3| 2008\n| ''[['Til Death]]''\n| Roxie\n| Episode: \"Raisinette in the Sun\"\n|-\n| ''[[Privileged (TV series)|Privileged]]''\n| Pam\n| Episode: \"All About the Haves and the Have-Nots\"\n|-\n| ''[[Merry Christmas, Drake & Josh]]''\n| Helen Dubois\n| Televis